      = 5\n| weight_lbs         = 220\n| high_school        = [[Perry Meridian High School|Perry Meridian]]<br>([[Indianapolis]], [[Indiana]])\n| college            = [[Ball State Cardinals football|Ball State]]\n| undraftedyear      = 1994\n| pastteams          =\n* [[1995 Calgary Stampeders season|Calgary Stampeders]] ({{CFL Year|1995}})\n* [[Orlando Predators]] ({{AFL Year|1996}})\n* [[Nashville Kats]] ({{AFL Year|1997}})\n| pastcoaching       =\n* [[Ball State Cardinals football|Ball State]] ([[Graduate assistant|GA]]) (1994)\n* Nashville Kats (QB) ({{AFL Year|1998}})\n* Nashville Kats (OC) ({{AFL Year|1999}})\n* [[Augusta Stallions]] ({{af2 Year|2000}})\n* [[Carolina Cobras]] ([[Offensive Coordinator|OC]]) ({{AFL Year|2001}})\n* Carolina Cobras ({{AFL Year|2001}}\u2013{{AFL Year|2002}})\n* [[New Orleans VooDoo]] ({{AFL Year|2004}}\u2013{{AFL Year|2008}})\n* [[New Orleans Saints]] (Scout) (2009\u20132011)\n* [[Tulane Green Wave football|Tulane]] (QB) (2012\u20132013)\n* New Orleans Saints (QB) (2014\u20132015)\n* Ball State (HC) (2016\u2013present)\n| highlights         = \n* [[Vern Smith Leadership Award|MAC Most Valuable Player]] (1993)\n* [[Mid-American Conference football individual awards#Offensive Player of the Year|MAC Offensive Player of the Year]] (1993)\n* [[Arena Football League Coach of the Year Award|AFL Coach of the Year]] (2004)\n|aflstatlabel1=Completions\n|aflstatvalue1=3\n|aflstatlabel2=Attempts\n|aflstatvalue2=4\n|aflstatlabel3=Yards\n|aflstatvalue3=22\n|aflstatlabel4=Touchdowns\n|aflstatvalue4=1\n|aflstatlabel5=Interceptions\n|aflstatvalue5=0\n| coachregrecord       = 39\u201340 ({{winpct|39|40}})\n| coachplayoffrecord   = 1\u20133 ({{winpct|1|3}})\n| coachrecord          = 40\u201343 ({{winpct|40|43}})\n| afl                = 1171\n}}\n\n'''Michael David Neu''' (born December 29, 1970) is and [[American football]] coach and former [[quarterback]], who is the current head football coach of the [[Ball State Cardinals football|Ball State Cardinals]]. He played [[college football]] at Ball State for [[Paul Schudel]] from 1990 to 1993 and played in the [[Canadian Football League]] (CFL) for one season and the [[Arena Football League]] (AFL) for 2 seasons from 1995 to 1997. He then served as the head coach of the [[af2]]'s [[Augusta Stallions]] (2000), the AFL's [[Carolina Cobras]] (2001\u20132002) and the [[New Orleans VooDoo]] (2004\u20132008).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.chatsports.com/ball-state-cardinals/a/source/a-neu-era-mike-neu-returns-home-as-ball-state-football-coach-12111819 |title=A Neu Era: Mike Neu returns home as Ball State football coach |date=January 11, 2016 |publisher=Chat Sports, Inc |work=www.chatsports.com |accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref> In 2016, Neu returned to his alma mater, Ball State.<ref>Dakota Crawford, [http://www.indystar.com/story/sports/college/2016/01/06/ball-state-closing-football-hire/78361068/ \"Ball State names Mike Neu head football coach\"], ''[[Indianapolis Star]]'', January 7, 2016.</ref>\n\nNeu was born in [[Indianapolis, Indiana]]. He attended high school in Indianapolis at [[Perry Meridian High School]]. In 1990, Neu enrolled at [[Ball State University]] and played quarterback for the Cardinals, starting for four seasons. As a senior in [[1993 Ball State Cardinals football team|1993]], he lead Ball State to the [[Mid-American Conference]] (MAC) championship, was named the MAC MVP and Offensive Player of the Year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oursportscentral.com/services/releases/?id=3112730 |title=New Orleans VooDoo Coach Mike Neu to be inducted into Ball State Hall of Fame |date=December 30, 2004 |publisher=OurSports Central |work=www.oursportscentral.com |accessdate=February 6, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, before pursuing a professional career, Neu would become a graduate assistant for Ball State. He would sign with the [[Calgary Stampeders]] of the [[Canadian Football League]], where he served as a backup to [[Doug Flutie]] in 1995. In 1996, Neu signed with the [[Orlando Predators]] of the [[Arena Football League]], where he spent the season as a backup to [[Pat O'Hara]]. He appeared in a single game for the Predators, throwing and rushing for touchdowns. The following year he signed with the [[Nashville Kats]], but never appeared in a single game.\n\nFrom 1998 to 1999, he would remain with the Kats, but in the roles of quarterbacks coach and offensive coordinator respectfully. In 2000, he turned to the [[af2]] as the head coach of the [[Augusta Stallions]]. Neu returned to the AFL ranks in 2001 as the offensive coordinator for the [[Carolina Cobras]]. When head coach [[Doug Kay]] resigned suddenly during the season, Neu was elevated to head coach of the Cobras, leading them to a Wild Card round loss to the [[Indiana Firebirds]]. After having the interim tag removed, Neu lead the Cobras to the AFL Semifinals, where they lost to AFL runner-up, [[Arizona Rattlers]]. After taking a year off, Neu was named the head coach of the [[New Orleans VooDoo]], lead them to a 2004 South Division Title. During the [[2006 Arena Football League season|2006 AFL season]], while the VooDoo suspended operations for the season, he worked as a [[Scout (sports)|professional scout]] for the [[National Football League]]'s [[New Orleans Saints]].\n\nIn 2014, Neu left his job as quarterbacks coach with the [[Tulane Green Wave football]] team, to take the same position with the Saints.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nola.com/tulane/index.ssf/2014/02/tulane_qb_coach_mike_neu_heade.html |title=New Orleans Saints confirm Tulane QB coach Mike Neu headed back to Saints as QB coach |author=Tammy Nunez |date=February 4, 2014 |publisher=NOLA Media Group |work=www.nola.com |accessdate=February 6, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Indianapolis]], [[Indiana]] on December 29, 1970, Neu is the son of Gwyndoline and Ed Neu.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.furnituretoday.com/business-news/obituaries-137/ |title=Obituaries |date=March 25, 2002 |publisher=BridgeTower Media |work=www.furnituretoday.com |accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref> He attended [[Perry Meridian High School]] in [[Indianapolis]], where was the starting quarterback.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wthr.com/article/kravitz-family-and-football-bring-ball-state-alum-mike-neu-back-to-muncie |title=KRAVITZ: Family and football bring Ball State alum Mike Neu back to Muncie |author=Bob Kravitz |date=September 2, 2016 |publisher= |work=www.wthr.com |accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref> He was named All-State as a senior in 1989. Neu grew up a fan of the [[University of Notre Dame]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ballstatedaily.com/article/2018/09/sports-football-notre-dame-preview |title=Head coach Mike Neu revisits childhood as Cardinals prepare to take on Irish |author=Zach Piatt |date=September 6, 2018 |publisher=Unified Student Media |work=www.ballstatedaily.com |accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Head coaching record==\n\n===College===\n{{CFB Yearly Record Start | type = coach | team = | conf = | bowl = no| poll = no}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name      = [[Ball State Cardinals football|Ball State Cardinals]]\n | conf      = [[Mid-American Conference]]\n | startyear = 2016\n | endyear   = \n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship =  \n | year         = [[2016 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2016]]\n | name         = [[2016 Ball State Cardinals football team|Ball State]]\n | overall      = 4\u20138 \n | conference   = 1\u20137\n | confstanding = 6th <small>(West)</small>\n | bowloutcome  = no\n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship =  \n | year         = [[2017 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2017]]\n | name         = [[2017 Ball State Cardinals football team|Ball State]]\n | overall      = 2\u201310 \n | conference   = 0\u20138 \n | confstanding = 6th <small>(West)</small>\n | bowloutcome  = no\n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n |