{"title_page": "Hindustani grammar", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2016}}\n\n[[Hindustani language|Hindustani]], the [[lingua franca]] of northern India and Pakistan, has two standardised [[Register (sociolinguistics)|register]]s: [[Hindi]] and [[Urdu]]. Grammatical differences between the two standards are minor but each uses its own script: Hindi uses [[Devanagari]] while Urdu uses [[Urdu alphabet|an extended form]] of the [[Perso-Arabic script]], typically in the [[Nasta\u02bfl\u012bq script|Nasta\u02bfl\u012bq]] style.\n\nOn this grammar page [[Hindustani language|Hindustani]] is written in \"standard [[oriental studies|orientalist]]\" [[Transcription (linguistics)|transcription]] as outlined in {{Harvcoltxt|Masica|1991|p=xv}}. Being \"primarily a system of [[transliteration]] from the Indian scripts, [and] based in turn upon [[Sanskrit]]\" (cf. [[IAST]]), these are its salient features: [[subscript]] [[dot (diacritic)|dot]]s for [[retroflex consonant]]s; [[Macron (diacritic)|macron]]s for etymologically, contrastively [[long vowel]]s; ''h'' for [[Aspiration (phonetics)|aspirated]] [[plosive]]s; and [[tilde]]s for [[nasalized vowel]]s.\n\n==Phonology==\n{{main|Hindustani phonology}}\nThe vowels used in Hindustani are the following: {{H:title|/\u0259/|''a''|dotted=no}}, {{H:title|/\u00e4\u02d0/|''\u0101''|dotted=no}}, {{H:title|/\u026a/|''i''|dotted=no}}, {{H:title|/i\u02d0/|''\u012b''|dotted=no}}, {{H:title|/\u028a/|''u''|dotted=no}}, {{H:title|/u\u02d0/|''\u016b''|dotted=no}}, {{H:title|/e\u02d0/|''e''|dotted=no}}, {{H:title|/o\u02d0/|''o''|dotted=no}}, {{H:title|/\u025b\u02d0/|''ai''|dotted=no}}, {{H:title|/\u0254\u02d0/|''au''|dotted=no}}.  Note that the vowels ''a'' ''ai'' ''au'' normally have the pronunciations {{IPA|[\u0259] [\u025b\u02d0] [\u0254\u02d0]}}. [[Consonant]]s are outlined in the table below. Hovering the mouse cursor over them will reveal the appropriate [[International Phonetic Alphabet|IPA]] symbol, while in the rest of the article hovering the mouse cursor over {{H:title||underlined}} forms will reveal the appropriate English [[translation]]. \n\n:::{|class=\"wikitable IPA\" border=\"2\"\n!\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[Bilabial consonant|Bilabial]]\n! [[Labiodental consonant|Labio-<br>dental]]\n! colspan=\"2\" | &nbsp;[[Dental consonant|Dental]]&nbsp;\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[Alveolar consonant|Alveolar]]\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[Retroflex consonant|Retroflex]]\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[Post-alveolar|Post-alv.]]/<br>[[Palatal consonant|Palatal]]\n! colspan=\"2\" | &nbsp;[[Velar consonant|Velar]] &nbsp;\n! [[Uvular consonant|Uvular]]\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[Glottal consonant|Glottal]]\n|- align=center\n! [[Plosive]]\n| {{H:title|/p/|p|dotted=no}}<br>{{H:title|/p\u02b0/|ph|dotted=no}}\n| {{H:title|/b/|b|dotted=no}}<br>{{H:title|/b\u02b1/|bh|dotted=no}}\n|\n| {{H:title|/t\u032a/|t|dotted=no}}<br>{{H:title|/t\u032a\u02b0/|th|dotted=no}}\n| {{H:title|/d\u032a/|d|dotted=no}}<br>{{H:title|/d\u032a\u02b1/|dh|dotted=no}}\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n| {{H:title|/\u0288/|\u1e6d|dotted=no}}<br>{{H:title|/\u0288\u02b0/|\u1e6dh|dotted=no}}\n| {{H:title|/\u0256/|\u1e0d|dotted=no}}<br>{{H:title|/\u0256\u02b1/|\u1e0dh|dotted=no}}\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n| {{H:title|/k/|k|dotted=no}}<br>{{H:title|/k\u02b0/|kh|dotted=no}}\n| {{H:title|/\u0261/|g|dotted=no}}<br>{{H:title|/g\u02b1/|gh|dotted=no}}\n| {{H:title|/q/, often /k/ in Hindi|(q)|dotted=no}}\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n|-align=center\n! [[Affricate consonant|Affricate]]\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n| {{H:title|/t\u0283/|c|dotted=no}}<br>{{H:title|/t\u0283\u02b0/|ch|dotted=no}}\n| {{H:title|/d\u0292/|j|dotted=no}}<br>{{H:title|/d\u0292\u02b1/|jh|dotted=no}}\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n|- align=center\n! [[Nasal stop|Nasal]]\n| colspan=\"2\" | {{H:title|/m/|m|dotted=no}}\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" | {{H:title|/n/|n|dotted=no}}\n| colspan=\"2\" | {{H:title|[\u0273]|(\u1e47)|dotted=no}}\n| colspan=\"2\" | {{H:title|[\u0272]|(\u00f1)|dotted=no}}\n| colspan=\"2\" | {{H:title|[\u014b]|(\u1e45)|dotted=no}}\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n|- align=center\n! [[Fricative]]\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n| {{H:title|/f/|f|dotted=no}}\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n| {{H:title|/s/|s|dotted=no}}\n| {{H:title|/z/|z|dotted=no}}\n| colspan=\"2\" | {{H:title|/\u0283/; [\u0282] before /\u0288, \u0288\u02b0/|(\u1e63)|dotted=no}}\n| {{H:title|/\u0283/|\u015b|dotted=no}}\n| {{H:title|/\u0292/|(\u017a)|dotted=no}}\n| {{H:title|/x/, often [k\u02b0] in Hindi|(x)|dotted=no}}\n| {{H:title|/\u0263/, often [g] in Hindi|(\u0121)|dotted=no}}\n|\n\n| colspan=\"2\" | {{H:title|/\u0266/|h|dotted=no}}\n|- align=center\n! [[Flap consonant|Tap or Flap]]\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" | {{H:title|/\u027e/|r|dotted=no}}\n| colspan=\"2\" | {{H:title|[\u027d]|(\u1e5b)|dotted=no}}<br>{{H:title|[\u027d\u02b1]|(\u1e5bh)|dotted=no}}\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n|- align=center\n! [[Approximant]]\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n| {{H:title|/\u028b/|v|dotted=no}}\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" | {{H:title|/j/|y|dotted=no}}\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n|- align=center\n! [[Lateral approximant|Lateral<br>approximant]]\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" | {{H:title|/l/|l|dotted=no}}\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n|- align=center\n|}\n\n==Morphology==\n\n===Nouns===\nHindustani distinguishes two [[grammatical gender|genders]] (masculine and feminine), two noun types ([[count noun|count]] and non-count), two [[grammatical number|numbers]] (singular and plural), and three [[grammatical case|case]]s ([[direct case|direct]], [[oblique case|oblique]], and [[vocative case|vocative]]).<ref name=\"Kachru\">{{cite book|last1=Kachru|first1=Yamuna|title=Hindi|date=2006|publisher=John Benjamins Publishing Company|edition=12th|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Hindi.html?id=ooH5VfLTQEQC|isbn=9789027238122}}</ref>{{rp|43}} Nouns may be further divided into two classes based on [[declension]], called type-I (marked) and type-II (unmarked). The basic difference between the two categories is that the former has characteristic [[suffix|termination]]s in the direct singular while the latter does not.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Shapiro|2003|pp=262\u2013263}}</ref>\n\nThe table below displays the suffix paradigms. A [[hyphen]] symbol (for the marked type-I) denotes change from the original termination to another (for example ''la\u1e5bk\u0101'' to ''la\u1e5bke'' in the masculine singular oblique), whereas a [[Plus and minus signs|plus]] sign (for the unmarked type-II) denotes an ending which should be added (''seb'' to ''seb\u00f5'' in the masculine plural oblique).\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" colspan=\"2\"| !! colspan=\"2\"| Singular !! colspan=\"3\"| Plural\n|-\n! Direct !! Oblique/Vocative !! Direct !! Oblique !! Vocative\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Masculine !! I\n| -''\u0101''<br>\u0640\u0627<br>\u093e||colspan=\"2\"|-''e''<br>\u0947/\u0640\u06d2||-''\u00f5''<br>\u094b\u0902/\u0640\u0648\u06ba||-''o''<br>\u094b/\u0640\u0648\n|-\n! II\n|colspan=\"3\"| ||+''\u00f5''<br>\u094b\u0902/\u0640\u0648\u06ba||+''o''<br>\u094b/\u0640\u0648\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Feminine !! I\n|colspan=\"2\"|-''\u012b''<br>\u0940/\u0640\u0650\u06cc<br>-''i''<br>\u093f/\u0640\u0650\u06cc<br>-''iy\u0101''<br>\u092f\u093e\u093f/\u0640\u0650\u06cc\u0627||-''iy\u0101\u0303''<br>\u092f\u093e\u093f\u0901/\u0640\u0650\u06cc\u0627\u06ba||-''iy\u00f5''<br>\u092f\u094b\u093f\u0902/\u0640\u0650\u06cc\u0648\u06ba||-''iyo''<br>\u092f\u094b\u093f/\u0640\u0650\u06cc\u0648\n|-\n! II\n|colspan=\"2\"| ||+''\u1ebd''<br>\u0947\u0902/\u0640\u06cc\u06ba||+''\u00f5''<br>\u094b\u0902/\u0640\u0648\u06ba||+''o''<br>\u094b/\u0640\u0648\n|}\n\nThe next table of noun [[declension]]s, mostly adapted from {{Harvcoltxt|Shapiro|2003|p=263}}, shows the above suffix paradigms in action. Words: ''la\u1e5bk\u0101'' \u0932\u0921\u093c\u0915\u093e/\u0644\u0691\u06a9\u0627 ('boy'), ''ku\u0101\u0303'' \u0915\u0941\u0906\u0901/\u06a9\u0648\u0627\u06ba ('[[Water well|well]]'), ''seb'' \u0938\u0947\u092c/\u0633\u06cc\u0628 ('apple'), ''v\u0101lid'' \u0935\u0932\u093f\u0926/\u0648\u0627\u0644\u062f ('father'), ''c\u0101q\u016b'' \u091a\u093e\u0915\u093c\u0942/\u0686\u0627\u0642\u0648 ('[[penknife]]'), ''\u0101dm\u012b'' \u0906\u0926\u092e\u0940/\u0622\u062f\u0645\u06cc ('man'), ''mitr\u0101'' \u092e\u093f\u0924\u094d\u0930\u093e/\u0645\u062a\u0631\u0627 ('friend'), ''la\u1e5bk\u012b'' \u0932\u0921\u093c\u0915\u0940/\u0644\u0691\u06a9\u06cc ('girl'), ''ci\u1e5biy\u0101'' \u091a\u093f\u0921\u093c\u093f\u092f\u093e/\u0686\u0691\u06cc\u0627 ('[[finch]]'), ''kit\u0101b'' \u0915\u093f\u0924\u093e\u092c/\u06a9\u062a\u0627\u0628 ('book'), ''bh\u0101\u1e63\u0101'' \u092d\u093e\u0937\u093e/\u0628\u06be\u0627\u0634\u0627 ('language'), and ''aurat'' \u0914\u0930\u0924/\u0639\u0648\u0631\u062a ('woman').\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" colspan=\"2\"| !! colspan=\"2\"| Singular !! colspan=\"3\"| Plural\n|-\n! Direct !! Oblique/Vocative !! Direct !! Oblique !! Vocative\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Masculine !! I\n|''la\u1e5bk\u0101'' \u0932\u0921\u093c\u0915\u093e/\u0644\u0691\u06a9\u0627<br>''ku\u0101\u0303''<br>\u0915\u0941\u0906\u0901/\u06a9\u0648\u0627\u06ba {{ref|2|2}}\n|colspan=\"2\"|''la\u1e5bke'' \u0932\u0921\u093c\u0915\u0947/\u0644\u0691\u06a9\u06d2<br>''ku\u1ebd'' \u0915\u0941\u090f\u0901/\u06a9\u0648\u06cc\u06ba\n|''la\u1e5bk\u00f5'' >\u0932\u0921\u093c\u0915\u094b\u0902/\u0644\u0691\u06a9\u0648\u06ba<br>''ku\u00f5'' \u0915\u0941\u0913\u0902/\u06a9\u0648\u0648\u06ba\n|''la\u1e5bko'' \u0932\u0921\u093c\u0915\u094b/\u0644\u0691\u06a9\u0648\n|-\n! II\n|colspan=\"3\"|''seb'' \u0938\u0947\u092c/\u0633\u06cc\u0628<br>''v\u0101lid'' \u0935\u0932\u093f\u0926/\u0648\u0627\u0644\u062f {{ref|3|3}}<br>''c\u0101q\u016b'' \u091a\u093e\u0915\u093c\u0942/\u0686\u0627\u0642\u0648<br>''\u0101dm\u012b'' \u0906\u0926\u092e\u0940/\u0622\u062f\u0645\u06cc\n|''seb\u00f5'' \u0938\u0947\u092c\u094b\u0902/\u0633\u06cc\u0628\u0648\u06ba<br>''v\u0101lid\u00f5'' \u0935\u0932\u093f\u0926\u094b\u0902/\u0648\u0627\u0644\u062f\u0648\u06ba<br>''c\u0101qu\u00f5'' \u091a\u093e\u0915\u093c\u0942\u094b\u0902/\u0686\u0627\u0642\u0648\u0648\u06ba {{ref|4|4}}<br>''\u0101dmiy\u00f5'' \u0906\u0926\u094d\u092e\u093f\u092f\u094b\u0902/\u0622\u062f\u0645\u06cc\u0648\u06ba {{ref|4|4}}\n|<br>''pit\u0101o'' \u092a\u093f\u0924\u093e\u0913/\u067e\u062a\u0627\u0626\u0648<br><br>''\u0101dmiyo'' \u0906\u0926\u094d\u092e\u093f\u092f\u094b/\u0622\u062f\u0645\u06cc\u0648\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Feminine !! I\n|colspan=\"2\"|''la\u1e5bk\u012b'' \u0932\u0921\u093c\u0915\u0940/\u0644\u0691\u06a9\u06cc<br>''ci\u1e5biy\u0101'' \u091a\u093f\u0921\u093c\u093f\u092f\u093e/\u0686\u0691\u06cc\u0627\n|''la\u1e5bkiy\u0101\u0303'' \u0932\u0921\u093c\u0915\u093f\u092f\u093e\u0901/\u0644\u0691\u06a9\u06cc\u0627\u06ba<br>''ci\u1e5biy\u0101\u0303'' \u091a\u093f\u0921\u093c\u093f\u092f\u093e\u0901/\u0686\u0691\u06cc\u0627\u06ba\n|''la\u1e5bkiy\u00f5'' \u0932\u0921\u093c\u0915\u093f\u092f\u094b\u0902/\u0644\u0691\u06a9\u06cc\u0648\u06ba<br>''ci\u1e5biy\u00f5'' \u091a\u093f\u0921\u093c\u093f\u092f\u094b\u0902/\u0686\u0691\u06cc\u0648\u06ba\n|''la\u1e5bkiyo'' \u0932\u0921\u093c\u0915\u093f\u092f\u094b/\u0644\u0691\u06a9\u06cc\u0648\n|-\n! II\n|colspan=\"2\"|''kit\u0101b'' \u0915\u093f\u0924\u093e\u092c/\u06a9\u062a\u0627\u0628<br>''bh\u0101\u1e63\u0101'' \u092d\u093e\u0937\u093e/\u0628\u06be\u0627\u0634\u0627<br>''aurat'' \u0914\u0930\u0924/\u0639\u0648\u0631\u062a\n|''kit\u0101b\u1ebd'' \u0915\u093f\u0924\u093e\u092c\u0947\u0902/\u06a9\u062a\u0627\u0628\u06cc\u06ba<br>''bh\u0101\u1e63\u0101\u1ebd'' \u0915\u093f\u0924\u093e\u092c\u090f\u0901/\u0628\u06be\u0627\u0634\u0627\u0626\u06cc\u06ba{{ref|5|5}}<br>''aurt\u1ebd'' \u0914\u0930\u0924\u0947\u0902/\u0639\u0648\u0631\u062a\u06cc\u06ba\n|''kit\u0101b\u00f5'' \u0915\u093f\u0924\u093e\u092c\u094b\u0902/\u06a9\u062a\u0627\u0628\u0648\u06ba<br>''bh\u0101\u1e63\u0101\u00f5'' \u0915\u093f\u0924\u093e\u092c\u0913\u0902/\u0628\u06be\u0627\u0634\u0627\u0626\u0648\u06ba<br>''aurt\u00f5'' \u0914\u0930\u0924\u094b\u0902/\u0639\u0648\u0631\u062a\u0648\u06ba\n|<br><br>''aurto'' \u0914\u0930\u0924\u094b/\u0639\u0648\u0631\u062a\u0648\n|}\nNotes for noun declension:\n*{{note|1|1}}This is also the ending used for the vocative masculine singular.\n*{{note|2|2}}A small number of marked masculines like ku\u00e3\u0304 display [[nasalization]] of all terminations.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Shapiro|2003|p=262}}</ref>\n*{{note|3|3}}Some masculines ending in ''\u0101'' don't change in the direct plural and fall in the unmarked category. i.e. ''v\u0101lid'' \"father\", ''c\u0101c\u0101'' \"[[uncle]]\", ''r\u0101j\u0101'' \"[[king]]\".<ref name=\"Snell&Weightman1989p24\">{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|p=24}}</ref>\n*{{note|4|4}}Unmarked nouns ending in ''\u016b'' and ''\u012b'' generally shorten this to ''u'' and ''i'' before the oblique (and vocative) plural termination(s), with the latter also inserting the [[semivowel]] ''y''.<ref name=\"Snell&Weightman1989p24\" /><ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|p=43}}</ref><ref name=\"Shapiro2003p263\">{{Harvcoltxt|Shapiro|2003|p=263}}</ref>\n*{{note|5|5}}Many feminine [[Sanskrit]] loanwords such as ''bh\u0101\u1e63\u0101'' ('language') and ''m\u0101t\u0101'' (mother) end in ''\u0101'', therefore the ''\u0101'' is not a reliable indicator of noun gender.<ref name=\"Snell&Weightman1989p24\" />\n*The ''iy\u0101'' ending is also not a reliable indicator of gender or noun type. Some words such as ''pahiy\u0101'' ('wheel') and [[Persian language|Persian]] ''takiy\u0101'' ('pillow') are masculine type-I: ''pahiye'' ('wheels'), ''takiye'' ('pillows'). Feminine loanwords such as [[Arabic language|Arabic]] ''duniy\u0101'' ('world') and [[Sanskrit]] ''kriy\u0101'' ('action') use feminine type-II endings: ''duniy\u0101\u1ebd'' ('worlds'), ''kriy\u0101\u1ebd'' ('actions').\n*In Urdu, many Arabic words retain their Arabic plurals.\n*[[Persian language|Perso]]-[[Arabic language|Arabic]] [[loanword|loan]]s ending in final unpronounced ''h'' are handled as masculine marked nouns.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Schmidt|2003|p=313}}</ref> Hence ''bacca(h)'' \u2192 ''bacc\u0101''. The former is the Urdu spelling, the latter the Hindi.\n*Some Arabic loans may use their original [[Dual (grammatical number)|dual]] and [[plural]] markings. i.e. ''v\u0101lid'' \"father\" \u2192 ''v\u0101lidain'' \"[[parent]]s\".\n\n===Adjectives===\n[[Adjective]]s may be divided into '''declinable''' and '''indeclinable''' categories.<ref name=\"Shapiro2003p264\">{{Harvcoltxt|Shapiro|2003|p=264}}</ref> Declinables are marked, through termination, for the gender, number, case of the nouns they qualify. The set of declinable adjective terminations is similar but greatly simplified in comparison to that of noun terminations \u2014\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto;\"\n! colspan=\"2\"| !! Dir. sg. !! All else\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Decl. !! Masc.\n| -''\u0101''||-''e''\n|-\n! Fem.\n|colspan=\"2\"|-''\u012b''\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"| Indecl.\n|colspan=\"2\"|\n|}\n\nIndeclinable adjectives are completely invariable, and can end in either [[consonant]]s or [[vowel]]s (including ''\u0101'' and ''\u012b ''). A number of declinables display nasalization of all terminations.<ref name=\"Shapiro2003p264\"/> Dir. masc. sg. (''-\u0101'') is the [[citation form]].\n\n*Examples of declinable adjectives: ''ba\u1e5b\u0101'' \"big\", ''cho\u1e6d\u0101'' \"small\", ''mo\u1e6d\u0101'' \"fat\", ''acch\u0101'' \"good\", ''bur\u0101'' \"bad\", ''k\u0101l\u0101'' \"black\", ''\u1e6dha\u1e47\u1e0d\u0101'' \"cold\".\n*Examples of indeclinable adjectives: ''xar\u0101b'' \"bad\", ''s\u0101f'' \"clean\", ''bh\u0101r\u012b'' \"heavy\", ''murd\u0101'' \"dead\", ''sundar'' \"beautiful\", ''p\u0101gal'' \"crazy\", ''l\u0101l'' \"red\".\n\n{|\n|-\n|\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; margin: 1em auto 1em auto;\"\n|+Declinable adjective ''ba\u1e5b\u0101'' \"big\" in attributive use\n! rowspan=\"2\" colspan=\"2\"| !! colspan=\"2\"| Sg. !! colspan=\"3\"| Pl.\n|-\n! Dir. !! Obl. !! Dir. !! Obl. !! Voc.\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| M !! I\n|''ba\u1e5b\u0101 la\u1e5bk\u0101''<br>''ba\u1e5b\u0101 ku\u0101\u0303''\n|colspan=\"2\"|''ba\u1e5be la\u1e5bke''<br>''ba\u1e5be ku\u1ebd''\n|''ba\u1e5be la\u1e5bk\u00f5''<br>''ba\u1e5be ku\u00f5''\n|''ba\u1e5be la\u1e5bko''\n|-\n! II\n|''ba\u1e5b\u0101 seb''<br>''ba\u1e5b\u0101 pit\u0101''<br>''ba\u1e5b\u0101 c\u0101k\u016b''<br>''ba\u1e5b\u0101 \u0101dm\u012b''<br>''ba\u1e5b\u0101 mitra''\n|colspan=\"2\"|''ba\u1e5be seb''<br>''ba\u1e5be pit\u0101''<br>''ba\u1e5be c\u0101k\u016b''<br>''ba\u1e5be \u0101dm\u012b''<br>''ba\u1e5be mitra''\n|''ba\u1e5be seb\u00f5''<br>''ba\u1e5be pit\u0101\u00f5''<br>''ba\u1e5be c\u0101ku\u00f5''<br>''ba\u1e5be \u0101dmiy\u00f5''<br>''ba\u1e5be mitr\u00f5''\n|<br>''ba\u1e5be pit\u0101o''<br><br>''ba\u1e5be \u0101dmiyo''<br>''ba\u1e5be mitro''\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| F !! I\n|colspan=\"2\"|''ba\u1e5b\u012b la\u1e5bk\u012b''<br>''ba\u1e5b\u012b \u015bakti''<br>''ba\u1e5b\u012b ci\u1e5biy\u0101''\n|''ba\u1e5b\u012b la\u1e5bkiy\u0101\u0303''<br>''ba\u1e5b\u012b \u015baktiy\u0101\u0303''<br>''ba\u1e5b\u012b ci\u1e5biy\u0101\u0303''\n|''ba\u1e5b\u012b la\u1e5bkiy\u00f5''<br>''ba\u1e5b\u012b \u015baktiy\u00f5''<br>''ba\u1e5b\u012b ci\u1e5biy\u00f5''\n|''ba\u1e5b\u012b la\u1e5bkiyo''\n|-\n! II\n|colspan=\"2\"|''ba\u1e5b\u012b kit\u0101b''<br>''ba\u1e5b\u012b bh\u0101\u1e63\u0101''<br>''ba\u1e5b\u012b aurat''\n|''ba\u1e5b\u012b kit\u0101b\u1ebd''<br>''ba\u1e5b\u012b bh\u0101\u1e63\u0101\u1ebd''<br>''ba\u1e5b\u012b aurt\u1ebd''\n|''ba\u1e5b\u012b kit\u0101b\u00f5''<br>''ba\u1e5b\u012b bh\u0101\u1e63\u0101\u00f5''<br>''ba\u1e5b\u012b aurt\u00f5''\n|<br><br>''ba\u1e5b\u012b aurto''\n|}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; margin: 1em auto 1em auto;\"\n|+Indeclinable adjective ''xar\u0101b'' \"bad\" in attributive use\n! rowspan=\"2\" colspan=\"2\"| !! colspan=\"2\"| Sg. !! colspan=\"3\"| Pl.\n|-\n! Dir. !! Obl. !! Dir. !! Obl. !! Voc.\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| M !! I\n|''xar\u0101b la\u1e5bk\u0101''<br>''xar\u0101b ku\u0101\u0303''\n|colspan=\"2\"|''xar\u0101b la\u1e5bke''<br>''xar\u0101b ku\u1ebd''\n|''xar\u0101b la\u1e5bk\u00f5''<br>''xar\u0101b ku\u00f5''\n|''xar\u0101b la\u1e5bko''\n|-\n! II\n|colspan=\"3\"|''xar\u0101b seb''<br>''xar\u0101b pit\u0101''<br>''xar\u0101b c\u0101k\u016b''<br>''xar\u0101b \u0101dm\u012b''<br>''xar\u0101b mitra''\n|''xar\u0101b seb\u00f5''<br>''xar\u0101b pit\u0101\u00f5''<br>''xar\u0101b c\u0101ku\u00f5''<br>''xar\u0101b \u0101dmiy\u00f5''<br>''xar\u0101b mitr\u00f5''\n|<br>''xar\u0101b pit\u0101o''<br><br>''xar\u0101b \u0101dmiyo''<br>''xar\u0101b mitro''\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| F !! I\n|colspan=\"2\"|''xar\u0101b la\u1e5bk\u012b''<br>''xar\u0101b \u015bakti''<br>''xar\u0101b ci\u1e5biy\u0101''\n|''xar\u0101b la\u1e5bkiy\u0101\u0303''<br>''xar\u0101b \u015baktiy\u0101\u0303''<br>''xar\u0101b ci\u1e5biy\u0101\u0303''\n|''xar\u0101b la\u1e5bkiy\u00f5''<br>''xar\u0101b \u015baktiy\u00f5''<br>''xar\u0101b ci\u1e5biy\u00f5''\n|''xar\u0101b la\u1e5bkiyo''\n|-\n! II\n|colspan=\"2\"|''xar\u0101b kit\u0101b''<br>''xar\u0101b bh\u0101\u1e63\u0101''<br>''xar\u0101b aurat''\n|''xar\u0101b kit\u0101b\u1ebd''<br>''xar\u0101b bh\u0101\u1e63\u0101\u1ebd''<br>''xar\u0101b aurt\u1ebd''\n|''xar\u0101b kit\u0101b\u00f5''<br>''xar\u0101b bh\u0101\u1e63\u0101\u00f5''<br>''xar\u0101b aurt\u00f5''\n|<br><br>''xar\u0101b aurto''\n|}\n|}\n\nAll adjectives can be used either [[Attributive adjective#Attributive.2C predicative.2C absolute.2C and substantive adjectives|attributively, predicatively, or substantively]]. Substantively they are declined as nouns rather than adjectives.\n\n''s\u0101'' (~ ''se'' ~ ''s\u012b'') is a suffix for adjectives, modifying or lightening their meaning; giving them an \"-ish\" or \"quite\" sense. e.g. ''n\u012bl\u0101'' \"blue\" \u2192 ''n\u012bl\u0101-s\u0101'' \"bluish\". Its emphasis is rather ambiguous, sometimes enhancing, sometimes toning down, the sense of the adjective.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|p=117}}</ref>\n\n====Comparatives and superlatives====\n[[Comparative|Comparison]]s are made by using \"than\" (the [[postposition]] ''se''; [[Hindustani grammar#Postpositions|see below]]), \"more\" (''aur'', ''zy\u0101d\u0101''), and \"less\" (''kam''). The word for \"more\" is optional, while \"less\" is required, so that in the absence of either \"more\" will be inferred.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! Hindustani !! Word order !! Meaning\n|-\n|''G\u012bt\u0101 Gautam se lamb\u012b hai''||Gita Gautam than tall is||Gita is taller than Gautam\n|-\n|''G\u012bt\u0101 Gautam se aur/zy\u0101d\u0101 lamb\u012b hai''||Gita Gautam than more tall is||Gita is more tall than Gautam\n|-\n|''G\u012bt\u0101 Gautam jitn\u012b lamb\u012b hai''|| Gita Gautam as tall is\n||Gita is (just) as tall as Gautam\n|-\n|''G\u012bt\u0101 Gautam se kam lamb\u012b hai''||Gita Gautam than less tall is||Gita is less tall than Gautam\n|}\n\nIn the absence of an object of comparison (\"more\" of course is now no longer optional):\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! Hindustani !! Word order !! Meaning\n|-\n|''chokr\u0101 zy\u0101d\u0101 ba\u1e5b\u0101 hai''||The lad more big is||The lad is bigger\n|-\n|''chokr\u0101 utn\u0101 hi lamb\u0101 hai''|| The lad as just tall is\n||The lad is just as big\n|-\n|''chokr\u0101 kam ba\u1e5b\u0101 hai''||The lad less big is||The lad is less big\n|}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! Hindustani !! Word order !! Meaning\n|-\n|''zy\u0101d\u0101 ba\u1e5b\u0101 chokr\u0101''||The more big lad||The bigger lad\n|-\n|'' ''|| ||The just as big lad\n|-\n|''kam ba\u1e5b\u0101 chokr\u0101''||The less big lad ||The less big lad\n|}\n\n[[Superlative]]s are made through comparisons with \"all\" (''sab''). Comparisons using \"least\" are rare; it is more common to use an antonym.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! Hindustani !! Word order !! Meaning\n|-\n|''kamr\u0101 sabse s\u0101f hai''||The room all than clean is||The room is the cleanest\n|-\n|''kamr\u0101 sabse kam s\u0101f hai''||The room all than less clean is||The room is the least clean\n|-\n| ''kamr\u0101 sabse gand\u0101 hai''||The room all than dirty is||The room is the dirtiest\n|}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! Hindustani !! Word order !! Meaning\n|-\n|''sabse s\u0101f kamr\u0101''||The all than clean room||The cleanest room\n|-\n|''sabse kam s\u0101f kamr\u0101''||The all than less clean room||The least clean room\n|-\n|''sabse gand\u0101 kamr\u0101'' ||The all than dirty room||The dirtiest room\n|}\n\nIn Sanskritized and Persianized [[Register (sociolinguistics)|register]]s of Hindustani, comparative and superlative adjectival forms using suffixes derived from those languages can be found.<ref name=\"Shapiro 2003 265\">{{Harvcoltxt|Shapiro|2003|p=265}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! !! Sanskrit !! Persian\n|-\n|Comp. (\"-er\")||colspan=\"2\"|-''tar''\n|-\n|Sup. (\"-est\")||-''tam''||-''tar\u012bn''\n|}\n\n===Numerals===\n{{main|Hindustani numerals}}\nThe numeral systems of several of the Indo-Aryan languages, including Hindustani and [[Nepali language|Nepali]], are typical [[decimal]] systems, but contracted to the extent that nearly every number 1\u201399 is irregular. The first four [[ordinal number (linguistics)|ordinal numbers]] are also irregular. The suffix ''-v\u0101\u0303'' marks ordinals beginning at the number five.\n\n{| class=wikitable\n|+ 0-5\n! English !! Hindustani Cardinal !! Hindustani Ordinal\n|-\n| zero || ''\u015b\u016bnya'', ''sifar'' || -\n|-\n| one || ''ek'' || ''pahl\u0101'', ''avval''\n|-\n| two || ''do'' || ''d\u016bsr\u0101''\n|-\n| three || ''t\u012bn'' || ''t\u012bsr\u0101''\n|-\n| four || ''ch\u0101r'' || ''cauth\u0101''\n|-\n| five || ''p\u0101\u0303ch'' || ''p\u0101\u0303chv\u0101\u0303''\n|}\n\n===Postpositions===\nThe aforementioned [[inflection]]al [[grammatical case|case]] system only goes so far on its own, and rather serves as that upon which is built a system of [[agglutinative]] [[suffix]]es or [[Grammatical particle|particle]]s known as [[postposition]]s, which parallel [[English language|English]]'s [[preposition]]s. It is their use with a noun or verb that necessitates the noun or verb taking the oblique case (though the bare oblique is also minorly used [[adverb]]ially<ref name=\"Shapiro2003p266\">{{Harvcoltxt|Shapiro|2003|p=266}}</ref>), and it is with them that the locus of grammatical function or \"case-marking\" then lies. There are seven such one-word primary postpositions:\n\n*''k\u0101'' \u2013 [[Genitive case|genitive]] marker; variably declinable in the manner of an adjective. X ''k\u0101/ke/k\u012b'' Y has the sense \"X's Y\", with ''k\u0101/ke/k\u012b'' agreeing with Y.<ref name=\"Shapiro2003p264\"/>\n*''ko'' \u2013 marks the indirect [[Object (grammar)|object]] (hence named  \"[[dative]] marker\"), ''or'', if [[definiteness|definite]] or animate, the direct object.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|p=67}}</ref>\n*''ne'' \u2013 [[Ergative case|ergative]] marker; applied to [[Subject (grammar)|subject]]s of [[Transitivity (grammatical category)|transitive]] [[Perfective aspect|perfective]] [[verb]]s.\n*''se'' \u2013 [[Ablative case|ablative]] marker; has a very wide range of uses and meanings:\n**\"from\";  ''dill\u012b se'' \"from [[Delhi]]\".\n**\"from, of\"; ''{{IAST|tumse \u1e0darn\u0101}}'' \"to fear you\".\n**\"since\"; ''itv\u0101r se'' \"since Sunday\".\n**\"by, with\"; [[Instrumental case|instrumental]] marker.\n**\"by, with, -ly\"; [[adverb]]ial marker.\n**\"than\"; for [[comparative]]s.\n**a minority of verbs use ''se'' rather than ''ko'' to mark their [[Patient (grammar)|patient]]s.\n*''m\u1ebd'' \u2013 \"in\".\n*''par'' \u2013 \"on\".\n*''tak'' \u2013 \"until, up to\".\n\nBeyond these are a large range of compound postpositions, composed of the genitive primary postposition ''k\u0101'' in the oblique form (''ke'', ''k\u012b'') plus an adverb.\n\n*''k\u012b taraf'' \"towards\", ''ke andar'' \"inside\", ''ke \u0101ge'' \"in front of, ahead of\", ''ke \u016bpar'' \"on top of, above\", ''ke n\u012bce'' \"beneath, below\", ''ke p\u012bche'' \"behind\", ''ke b\u0101d'' \"after\", ''ke b\u0101re m\u1ebd'' \"about\", ''ke b\u0101har'' \"outside\", ''ke liye'' \"for\", ''ke s\u0101mne'' \"facing, opposite\", etc.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|pp=80\u201381}}</ref>\n\n===Pronouns===\n\n====Personal====\nHindustani has [[personal pronoun]]s for the first and second persons, while for the third person [[demonstrative]]s are used, which can be categorized [[Deixis|deictically]] as proximate and non-proximate.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Shapiro|2003|pp=264\u2013265}}</ref> [[Pronoun]]s distinguish [[Grammatical case|case]]s of [[Direct case|direct]], [[Oblique case|oblique]], and [[dative]]. The lattermost, often called a set of \"[[Contraction (grammar)|contracted]]\" forms, is in free variation with the oblique case plus dative [[postposition]]. Pronouns do not distinguish [[Grammatical gender|gender]].\n\nAlso displayed in the below table are the [[genitive]] pronominal forms to show that the 1st and 2nd pronouns have their own distinctive forms of ''mer\u0101'', ''ham\u0101r\u0101'',  ''ter\u0101'', ''tumh\u0101r\u0101'' apart from the regular formula of <small>OBL.</small> + ''k\u0101''; as well as the [[ergative case|ergative]] pronominal forms to show that the postposition ''ne'' does not straightforwardly suffix the oblique bases: rather than *''mujh ne'' and *''tujh ne'', direct bases are used giving ''mai ne'' and ''t\u016b ne'', and rather than ''in ne'' and ''un ne'', it's ''inh\u00f5 ne'' and ''unh\u00f5 ne''.\n\n''t\u016b'', ''tum'', and ''\u0101p'' are the three second person pronouns (\"you\"), constituting a threefold scale of sociolinguistic formality: respectively \"intimate\", \"familiar\", and \"polite\". The \"intimate\" is grammatically singular while the \"familiar\" and \"polite\" are grammatically plural.<ref name=\"Shapiro 2003 265\"/> When being referred to in the third person however, only those of the \"polite\" level of formality are grammatically plural.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|p=21}}</ref> The following table is adapted from {{Harvcoltxt|Shapiro|2003|p=265}}.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!rowspan=\"4\"|\n!colspan=\"5\"|Personal\n!colspan=\"4\"|Demonstrative\n!colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"3\"|Relative\n!colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"3\"|Interrogative\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|1st person\n!colspan=\"3\"|2nd person\n!colspan=\"4\"|3rd person\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Singular\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Plural\n!Singular\n!colspan=\"2\"|Plural\n!colspan=\"2\"|Proximal\n!colspan=\"2\"|Non-proximal\n|-\n!Intimate\n!Familiar\n!Polite\n!Singular\n!Plural\n!Singular\n!Plural\n!Singular\n!Plural\n!Singular\n!Plural\n|-\n!Direct\n|{{H:title|I|''m\u00e3\u0129''}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|{{H:title|we/us|''ham''}}\n|{{H:title|thou|''t\u016b''}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|{{H:title|you|''tum''}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|{{H:title|you|''\u0101p''}}\n|colspan=\"2\"|{{H:title|he/she/it/this/they/these|''ye''}}||colspan=\"2\"|{{H:title|he/she/it/that/they/those|''vo''}}\n|colspan=\"2\"|{{H:title|[those] who/[those] that|''jo''}}\n|colspan=\"2\"|{{H:title|who(?)|''kaun''}}, {{H:title|what(?)|''ky\u0101''}}\n|-\n!Oblique\n|{{H:title|me|''mujh''}}||{{H:title|thee|''tujh''}}||{{H:title|him/her/it/this|''is''}}||{{H:title|them/these|''in''}}||{{H:title|him/her/it/that|''us''}}||{{H:title|them/those|''un''}}||{{H:title|[he/she] whom/[that] which|''jis''}}||{{H:title|[those] whom/[those] which|''jin''}}||{{H:title|whom(?)/what(?)|''kis''}}||{{H:title|whom(?)/which ones(?)|''kin''}}\n|-\n!Dative\n|{{H:title|to me|''mujhe''}}||{{H:title|to us|''ham\u1ebd''}}||{{H:title|to thee|''tujhe''}}||{{H:title|to you|''tumh\u1ebd''}}||{{H:title|to you|''\u0101p ko''}}||{{H:title|to him/to her/to it/to this|''ise''}}||{{H:title|to them/to these|''inh\u1ebd''}}||{{H:title|to him/to her/to it/to that|''use''}}||{{H:title|to them/to those|''unh\u1ebd''}}\n|{{H:title|[he/she] to whom/[that] to which|''jise''}}||{{H:title|[those] to whom/[those] to which|''jinh\u1ebd''}}||{{H:title|to whom(?)/to what(?)|''kise''}}||{{H:title|to whom(?)/to which ones(?)|''kinh\u1ebd''}}\n|-\n!Genitive\n|{{H:title|My/Mine|''mer\u0101''}}||{{H:title|our(s)|''ham\u0101r\u0101''}}||{{H:title|thy/thine|''ter\u0101''}}\n|{{H:title|your(s)|''tumh\u0101r\u0101''}}||{{H:title|your/s|''\u0101p k\u0101''}}\n|{{H:title|his/her(s)/its/of this|''is k\u0101''}}||{{H:title|their(s)/of these|''in k\u0101''}}||{{H:title|his/her(s)/its/of that|''us k\u0101''}}||{{H:title|their(s)/of those|''un k\u0101''}}\n|{{H:title|[he/she] whose|''jis k\u0101''}}||{{H:title|[those] whose|''jin k\u0101''}}||{{H:title|whose(?)/which one's(?)|''kis k\u0101''}}||{{H:title|whose(?)/which ones'(?)|''kin k\u0101''}}\n|-\n!Ergative\n|{{H:title|I (have/had done something to an object)|''m\u00e3\u0129 ne''}}||{{H:title|we (have/had done something to an object)|''ham ne''}}||{{H:title|thou (hast/hadst done something to an object)|''t\u016b ne''}}||{{H:title|you (have/had done something to an object)|''tum ne''}}||{{H:title|you (have/had done something to an object)|''\u0101p ne''}}||{{H:title|he/she/it/this (has/had done something to an object)|''is ne''}}||{{H:title|they/these (have/had done something to an object)|''inh\u00f5 ne''}}\n|{{H:title|he/she/it/that (has/had done something to an object)|''us ne''}}||{{H:title|they/those (have/had done something to an object)|''unh\u00f5 ne''}}||{{H:title|[he/she] who/[that] which  (has/had done something to an object)|''jis ne''}}||{{H:title|[those] who/[those] that (have/had done something to an object)|''jinh\u00f5 ne''}}||{{H:title|who/what (has/had done something to an object?)|''kis ne''}}||{{H:title|who/which ones (has/have/had done something to an object?)|''kinh\u00f5 ne''}}\n|}\nNotes for pronouns:\n*Postpositions are treated as [[bound morpheme]]s after pronouns in Hindi, but as separate words in Urdu.<ref name=\"Schmidt2003p293\">{{Harvcoltxt|Schmidt|2003|p=293}}</ref> \n*The varying forms for the 3rd pn. dir. constitute one of the small number of grammatical differences between Hindi and Urdu. ''yah'' \"this\" / ''ye'' \"these\" / ''vah'' \"that\" / ''ve'' \"those\" is the ''literary'' set for Hindi while ''ye'' \"this, these\" / ''vo'' \"that, those\" is the set for Urdu and ''spoken'' (and also often written) Hindi.\n*The above [[Hindustani grammar#Postpositions|section on postpositions]] noted that ''ko'' (the dative case) marks direct objects if [[definiteness|definite]]. As \"the most specific thing of all is an individual\", persons (or their pronouns) nearly always take the dative case or postposition.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|p=68}}</ref>\n*it is very common practice to use plural pronouns (and their accompanying conjugation) in polite situations, thus ''tum'' can be used in the second person when referring to one person. Similarly, some speakers prefer plural ''ham'' over singular ''m\u00e3\u0129''. This is usually not quite the same as the \"[[Pluralis majestatis|royal we]]\"; it is rather colloquial.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|p=106}}</ref>\n*''ko\u012b'' and ''kuch'' are [[indefinite pronoun]]s/[[Quantifier (linguistics)|quantifier]]s. As pronouns ''ko\u012b'' is used for [[Animacy|animate]]s (\"someone\") and ''kuch'' for inanimates (\"something\").<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|p=88}}</ref> As quantifiers/adjectives ''ko\u012b'' is used for singular [[count noun]]s and ''kuch'' for [[mass noun]]s and plural count nouns. ''ko\u012b'' takes the form ''kis\u012b'' in the oblique. The form ''ka\u012b'' \"several\" is partially a plural equivalent to ''ko\u012b''.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|p=89}}</ref> ''kuch'' can also act as an [[adverb]], qualifying an adjective, meaning \"rather\". ''ko\u012b'' preceding a number takes the meaning of \"about, approximately\". In this usage it does not oblique to ''kis\u012b''.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|p=90}}</ref>\n*''apn\u0101'' is a (genitive) [[reflexive pronoun]]: \"my/your/etc. (own)\".<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|p=79}}</ref> Using non-reflexive and reflexive together gives emphasis; e.g. ''mer\u0101 apn\u0101'' \"my (very) own\".<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|p=80}}</ref> ''xud'', ''\u0101p'', and ''svayam'' are some (direct; non-genitive) others: \"my/your/etc.-self\".<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|p=198}}</ref> Bases for oblique usage are usually ''apne'' or ''apne \u0101p''. The latter alone can also mean \"of one's own accord\"; ''\u0101pas m\u1ebd'' means \"among/between themselves\".<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|p=199}}</ref>\n\n====Derivates====\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! rowspan=\"2\"| !! rowspan=\"2\"|Interrogative !! rowspan=\"2\"|Relative !! colspan=\"2\"|Demonstrative\n|-\n! Prox. !! Non-prox.\n|-\n!Time\n|{{H:title|when?|''kab''}}||{{H:title|when|''jab''}}\n|{{H:title|now|''ab''}}||{{H:title|then|''tab''}}\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Place\n|{{H:title|where?|''kah\u0101\u0303''}}||{{H:title|where|''jah\u0101\u0303''}}\n|{{H:title|here|''yah\u0101\u0303''}}||{{H:title|there|''vah\u0101\u0303''}}\n|-\n|{{H:title|whither?|''kidhar''}}||{{H:title|whither|''jidhar''}}\n|{{H:title|hither|''idhar''}}||{{H:title|thither|''udhar''}}\n|-\n!Quantity\n|{{H:title|how much/many?|''kitn\u0101''}}||{{H:title|as much/many|''jitn\u0101''}}\n|{{H:title|this much/many|''itn\u0101''}}||{{H:title|that much/many|''utn\u0101''}}\n|-\n!Quality\n|''kais\u0101''||''jais\u0101''||''ais\u0101''||''vais\u0101''\n|-\n!Manner\n|''kaise''||''jaise''||''aise''||''vaise''\n|}\n<!---gujarati677, schmidt323--->\n\n===Adverbs===\nHindustani has few underived forms.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Schmidt|2003|p=322}}</ref> [[Adverb]]s may be derived in ways such as the following \u2014\n*Simply obliquing some nouns and adjectives: ''n\u012bc\u0101'' \"low\" \u2192 ''n\u012bce'' \"down\", ''s\u012bdh\u0101'' \"straight\" \u2192 ''s\u012bdhe'' \"straight\", ''dh\u012br\u0101'' \"slow\" \u2192 ''dh\u012bre'' \"slowly\", ''sawer\u0101'' \"morning\" \u2192 ''sawere'' \"in the morning\", ''ye taraf'' \"this direction\" \u2192 ''is taraf'' \"in this direction\", ''kalkatt\u0101'' \"[[Calcutta]]\" \u2192 ''kalkatte'' \"to Calcutta\".\n*Nouns using a postposition such as ''se'' \"by, with, -ly\": ''zor'' \"force\" \u2192 ''zor se'' \"forcefully\" (lit. \"with force\"), ''dhy\u0101n'' \"attention\" \u2192 ''dhy\u0101n se'' \"attentively\" (lit. \"with attention\").\n*Adjectives using postpositional phrases involving \"way, manner\": ''acch\u0101'' \"good\" \u2192 ''acch\u012b tarah se'' \"well\" (lit. \"by/in a good way\"), ''x\u0101s'' \"special\" \u2192 ''x\u0101s taur par'' \"especially\" (lit. \"on a special way\").\n*Verbs in conjunctive form: ''h\u00e3s'' \"laugh\" \u2192 ''h\u00e3s kar'' \"laughingly\" (lit. \"having laughed\"), ''maharb\u0101n\u012b kar'' \"do kindness\" \u2192 ''maharb\u0101n\u012b kar ke'' \"kindly, please\" (lit. \"having done kindness\").<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|pp=150}}</ref>\n*Formative suffixes from Sanskrit or Perso-Arabic in higher registers of Hindi or Urdu. Skt. ''sambhava'' \"possible\" + ''{{IAST|-ta\u1e25}}'' \u2192 ''{{IAST|sambhavata\u1e25}}'' \"possibly; Ar. ''ittif\u0101q'' \"chance\" + ''-an'' \u2192 ''ittif\u0101qan'' \"by chance\".<ref name=\"Shapiro2003p266\"/>\n\n===Verbs===\n\n====Overview====\nThe Hindustani [[verb]]al system is largely structured around a combination of [[Grammatical aspect|aspect]] and [[Grammatical tense|tense]]/[[Grammatical mood|mood]]. Like the nominal system, the Hindustani verb involves successive layers of (inflectional) elements to the right of the [[Root (linguistics)|lexical base]].<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Masica|1991|p=257}}</ref>\n\nHindustani has 3 aspects: [[perfective]], [[habitual]], and [[Continuous and progressive aspects|continuous]], each having overt morphological correlates.<ref name=\"Shapiro2003p266\"/> These are [[participle]] forms, inflecting for [[Grammatical gender|gender]] and [[Grammatical number|number]] by way of a vowel termination, like adjectives.<ref name=\"Schmidt2003p323\"/> The perfective, though displaying a \"number of irregularities and morphophonemic adjustments\", is the simplest, being just the [[Word stem|verb stem]] followed by the agreement vowel. The habitual forms from the [[imperfective]] participle; verb stem, plus -''t''-, then vowel. The continuous forms [[Periphrasis|periphrastic]]ally through [[compound verb|compound]]ing ([[Hindustani grammar#Compounds|see below]]) with the perfective of ''rahn\u0101'' \"to stay\".\n\nDerived from ''hon\u0101'' \"to be\" are five [[copula (linguistics)|copula]] forms: [[Present tense|present]], [[Past tense|past]], [[subjunctive]], presumptive, [[contrafactual]] ([[List of acronyms and initialisms: A#AK|aka]] \"past conditional\"). Used both in basic predicative/existential sentences and as [[Auxiliary verb|verbal auxiliaries]] to aspectual forms, these constitute the basis of tense and mood.\n\nNon-aspectual forms include the [[infinitive]], the [[Imperative mood|imperative]], and the [[conjunction (grammar)|conjunctive]]. Mentioned morphological conditions such the subjunctive, \"presumptive\", etc. are applicable to both copula roots for auxiliary usage with aspectual forms ''and'' to non-copula roots directly for often unspecified (non-aspectual) [[Finite verb|finite]] forms.\n\n[[Finite verb]]al [[Agreement (linguistics)|agreement]] is with the nominative [[Subject (grammar)|subject]], except in the ''[[Transitive verb|transitive]] perfective'', where it is with the [[direct object]], with the erstwhile subject taking the [[ergative case|ergative]] construction ''-ne'' (see [[Hindustani grammar#Postpositions|postpositions]] above). The perfective aspect thus displays [[split ergativity]].\n\nTabled below on the left are the paradigms for adjectival [[Agreement (linguistics)|concord]] (<sup>A</sup>), here only slightly different from that introduced [[Hindustani grammar#Adjectives|previously]]: the f. pl. can nasalize under certain conditions. To the right are the paradigms for [[Grammatical person|personal]] concord (<sup>P</sup>), used by the subjunctive.\n\n{|\n|-\n|\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! (A) !! Sg. !! Pl.\n|-\n! Masc.\n| -''\u0101''||-''e''\n|-\n! Fem.\n| -''\u012b''||-''\u012b( \u0303)''\n|}\n|\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! (P) !! 1st. !! 2nd. !! 3rd.\n|-\n!Sg.\n| -''\u016b\u0303''||colspan=\"2\"|-''e''\n|-\n!Pl.\n| -''\u1ebd''|| -''o/\u1ebd''|| -''\u1ebd''\n|}\n|}\n\n====Forms====\nThe sample verb is intransitive ''dau\u1e5bn\u0101'' \"to run\", and the sample inflection is 3rd. masc. sg. (<sup>P</sup> = ''e'', <sup>A</sup> = ''\u0101'') where applicable.\n\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"10\" cellspacing=\"1\"\n|-\n! !!Non-aspectual !!Aspectual\n|-\n![[Non-finite verb|Non-finite]]\n|\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto\"\n!Root\n||{{mono|*}} ||{{H:title|run|''dau\u1e5b''}}\n|-\n!Infinitive/<br>Gerund/<br>Obligatory\n||{{mono|*-n\u0101}} ||{{H:title|to run / running|''dau\u1e5bn\u0101''}}\n|-\n!Obl. Infinitive\n||{{mono|*-ne}} ||''dau\u1e5bne''\n|-\n!Conjunctive\n||{{mono|*-kar, *-ke}} ||{{H:title|having run|''dau\u1e5bkar'', ''dau\u1e5bke''}}\n|-\n!Agentive/<br>Prospective\n||{{mono|*-ne v\u0101l-<sup>A</sup>, *-nev\u0101l-<sup>A</sup>}} ||{{H:title|runner / about to run|''dau\u1e5bne v\u0101l\u0101'', ''dau\u1e5bnev\u0101l\u0101''}}\n|}\n|\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto\"\n|+Adjectivals.\n!Perfective\n||{{mono|*-<sup>A</sup> (hu-<sup>A</sup>)}} ||{{H:title|run|''dau\u1e5b\u0101'' (''hu\u0101'')}}\n|-\n!Imperfective\n||{{mono|*-t-<sup>A</sup> (hu-<sup>A</sup>)}} ||{{H:title|running|''dau\u1e5bt\u0101'' (''hu\u0101'')}}\n|}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto\"\n|+Adverbial. Obl. of adjectival.\n|-\n!Imperfective\n||{{mono|*-t-e (hu-e)}} ||''dau\u1e5bte hue''\n|}\n|-\n!Finite\n|\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto\"\n|-\n!Contingent Future\n||{{mono|*-<sup>P</sup>}} ||{{H:title|(if ...) were to run / (then ...) will run|''dau\u1e5be''}}\n|-\n!Definite Future\n||{{mono|*-<sup>P</sup>-g-<sup>A</sup>}} ||{{H:title|will run|''dau\u1e5beg\u0101''}}\n|}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto\"\n|+Imperatives.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Shapiro|2003|p=268}}</ref>\n|-\n!Intimate\n||{{mono|*}} ||''dau\u1e5b''\n|-\n!Familiar\n||{{mono|*-o}} ||''dau\u1e5bo''\n|-\n!Polite\n||{{mono|*-iye}} ||''dau\u1e5biye''\n|-\n!Deferred\n||{{mono|*-n\u0101}} ||''dau\u1e5bn\u0101''\n|-\n!Deferential\n||{{mono|*-iye g\u0101}} ||''dau\u1e5biye g\u0101''\n|}\n|\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto\"\n|+Aspectuals plotted against copulas.\n! colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\"| !! Perfective !! Habitual !! Continuous\n|-\n|{{mono|*-<sup>A</sup>}}\n|{{mono|*-t-<sup>A</sup>}}\n|{{mono|* rah-<sup>A</sup>}}\n|-\n!Present\n|{{mono|[[#endnote_10|h-?]]}}\n|{{H:title|has run|''dau\u1e5b\u0101 hai''}}\n|{{H:title|runs|''dau\u1e5bt\u0101 hai''}}\n|{{H:title|is running|''dau\u1e5b rah\u0101 hai''}}\n|-\n!Past\n|{{mono|{{H:title|was; were|th-<sup>A</sup>}}}}\n|{{H:title|had run|''dau\u1e5b\u0101 th\u0101''}}\n|{{H:title|used to run|''dau\u1e5bt\u0101 th\u0101''}}\n|{{H:title|was running|''dau\u1e5b rah\u0101 th\u0101''}}\n|-\n!Subjunctive\n|{{mono|[[#endnote_10|ho-<sup>P</sup>]]}}\n|{{H:title|(if ...) has run|''dau\u1e5b\u0101 ho''}}\n|{{H:title|(if ...) runs (regularly)|''dau\u1e5bt\u0101 ho''}}\n|{{H:title|(if ...) is running|''dau\u1e5b rah\u0101 ho''}}\n|-\n!Presumptive\n|{{mono|{{H:title|must be|ho-<sup>P</sup> g-<sup>A</sup>}}}}\n|{{H:title|has presumably run|''dau\u1e5b\u0101 ho g\u0101''}}\n|{{H:title|presumably runs|''dau\u1e5bt\u0101 ho g\u0101''}}\n|{{H:title|is presumably running|''dau\u1e5b rah\u0101 ho g\u0101''}}\n|-\n!Contrafactual\n|{{mono|ho-t-<sup>A</sup>}}\n|{{H:title|(if ...) had run / (then ...) would have run|''dau\u1e5b\u0101 hot\u0101''}}\n|{{H:title|(if ...) used to run / (then ...) would have run (regularly)|''dau\u1e5bt\u0101 hot\u0101''}}\n|{{H:title|(if ...) had been running / (then ...) would have been running|''dau\u1e5b rah\u0101 hot\u0101''}}\n|-\n!Unspecified\n|\n|{{H:title|ran|''dau\u1e5b\u0101''}}\n|''dau\u1e5bt\u0101''\n|\n|}\n|}\n\n'''Notes'''\n*Much of the above chart information derives from {{Harvcoltxt|Masica|1991|pp=292\u2013294, 323\u2013325}}.\n*The future tense is formed by adding the suffix ''g\u0101'' (~ ''ge'' ~ ''g\u012b'') to the subjunctive, which is a contraction of ''ga\u0101'' (= ''gay\u0101'', perfective participle of ''j\u0101n\u0101'' \"to go\").<ref name=\"Schmidt2003p323\">{{Harvcoltxt|Schmidt|2003|p=323}}</ref> The future suffix, conjunctive participle, and suffix ''v\u0101l\u0101'' are treated as bound morphemes in written Hindi, but as separate words in written Urdu.<ref name=\"Schmidt2003p293\"/> \n*{{note|10}}The present copula ({{mono|h-?}}) seems not to follow along the lines of the regular <sup>P</sup> system of terminations; while the subjunctive copula ({{mono|ho-<sup>P</sup>}}) is thoroughly irregular. So here are all of their forms.\n:{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! rowspan=\"2\"| !!colspan=\"3\"| Sg !! colspan=\"4\"| Pl.\n|-\n! 1st. !! 2nd. !! 3rd. !! 1st. !! colspan=\"2\"| 2nd. !! 3rd.\n|-\n! Pron. !! ''m\u00e3\u0129'' !! ''t\u016b'' !! ''vo'' !! ''ham'' !! ''tum'' !! ''\u0101p'' !! ''vo''\n|-\n! Pres.\n|{{H:title|am|''h\u016b\u0303''}}||colspan=\"2\"|{{H:title|are, is|''hai''}}||{{H:title|are|''h\u00e3\u0129''}}\n|{{H:title|are|''ho''}}||colspan=\"2\"|{{H:title|are|''h\u00e3\u0129''}}\n|-\n! Subj.\n|''h\u016b\u0303''||colspan=\"2\"|''ho''||''h\u00f5''||''ho''||colspan=\"2\"|''h\u00f5''\n|}\n*For the 1. subj. sg. copula {{Harvcoltxt|Schmidt|2003|pp=324}} and {{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|pp=113, 125}} list ''h\u016b\u0303'' while {{Harvcoltxt|Shapiro|2003|p=267}} lists ''ho\u016b\u0303''.\n*{{Harvcoltxt|Shapiro|2003|p=268}} lists the polite imperative ending as ''-iye'', while {{Harvcoltxt|Schmidt|2003|p=330}} lists it as ''-ie'' but ''-iye'' after ''\u0101, o, \u016b''.\n*The euphonic [[Semivowel|glide]] ''y'' is inserted in perfective participles between prohibited [[vowel cluster]]s. It is historically the remnant of the old perfective marker.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Schmidt|2003|pp=324}}</ref> The clusters are ''a + \u0101'', ''\u0101 + \u0101'', ''o + \u0101'', and ''\u012b + \u0101'', resulting in ''\u0101y\u0101'', ''ay\u0101'', ''oy\u0101'', ''iy\u0101''.<ref name=\"Schmidt2003p328\"/> e.g. ''kh\u0101'''y'''\u0101/kh\u0101'''y'''e/kh\u0101\u012b/kh\u0101\u012b\u0303'' (''kh\u0101''- \"eat\").\n*In addition, the combinations ''\u012b + \u012b'' and ''i + \u012b'' give ''\u012b''.<ref name=\"Schmidt2003p328\"/> e.g. ''piy\u0101/piye/p'''\u012b'''/p'''\u012b\u0303''''' (''p\u012b-'' \"drink\").\n*As stated, agreement in the transitive perfective is with the direct object, with the erstwhile subject taking the ergative postposition ''ne''. If however the direct object takes the postposition ''ko'' (marking [[definiteness]]), or if no direct object is expressed, then agreement neutralizes to default m. sg. ''-\u0101''.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|p=140}}</ref>\n*Is this regard, there are a small number of verbs that while perhaps logically transitive still do not take ''ne'' and continue to agree with the subject, in the perfective. e.g. ''l\u0101n\u0101'' \"to bring\", ''bh\u016bln\u0101'' \"to forget\", ''miln\u0101'' \"to meet\", etc.\n<!--- perhaps Ergative points belong to Syntax\nalso discuss: forms both intransitive/transitive\n--->\n*Besides supplying the copulas, ''hon\u0101'' \"to be\" can be used aspectually: ''hu\u0101'' \"happened, became\"; ''hot\u0101'' \"happens, becomes, is\"; ''ho rah\u0101'' \"happening, being\".\n*''-ke'' can be used as a colloquial alternative to ''-kar'' for the conjunctive participle of any verb.  But for ''karn\u0101'' it is the only possible form; ''karke'', not *''karkar''.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|p=149}}</ref>\n*Hindustani displays a very small number of irregular forms, spelled out in the cells below.\n:{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Root !! rowspan=\"2\"| Perf.<br>Stem<br><ref name=\"Schmidt2003p328\">{{Harvcoltxt|Schmidt|2003|p=328}}</ref> !! colspan=\"2\"| Imperative<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|p=64}}</ref>\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Subj.<br>Stem<br><ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|pp=113, 125}}</ref>\n|-\n!Fam. !!Pol.\n|-\n|''ho-'' \"be\"||''hu-''|| || ||\n|-\n|''j\u0101-'' \"go\"||''ga-''{{ref|7}}|| || ||\n|-\n|''kar-'' \"do\"||''ki-''|| ||''k\u012bjie'' ||\n|-\n|''de-'' \"give\"||''di-''||''do''||''d\u012bjie''||''d-''\n|-\n|''le-'' \"take\"||''li-''||''lo''||''l\u012bjie''||''l-''\n|-\n|''p\u012b-'' \"drink\"|| || ||''p\u012bjie''\n|}\n*{{note|7}} However, it is ''j\u0101-'' that is used as the perfective stem in the rare instance of an intransitive verb like ''j\u0101n\u0101'' being expressed passively, such as in a passivized imperative/subjunctive construction: ''ghar j\u0101y\u0101 j\u0101e?'' \"Shall [we] go home?\" (lit. \"Shall home be gone to [by us]?\").<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|p=179}}</ref>\n\n====Causatives====\nTransitives or [[causative]]s are morphologically contrastive in Hindustani, leading to the existence of related verb sets divisible along such lines. While the derivation of such forms shows patterns, they do reach a level of variegation so as to make it somewhat difficult to outline all-encompassing rules. Furthermore, some sets may have as many as four to five distinct members; also, the meaning of certain members of given sets may be idiosyncratic.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Shapiro|2003|p=270}}</ref>\n\nStarting from intransitive or transitive verb stems further transitive/causative stems are produced according to these assorted rules \u2014\n:1a. Root vowel change: ''a'' \u2192 ''\u0101'', ''u/\u016b'' \u2192 ''o'', ''i/\u012b'' \u2192 ''e''. Sometimes accompanied by root final consonant change: ''k'' \u2192 ''c'', ''{{IAST|\u1e6d}}'' \u2192 ''{{IAST|\u1e5b}}'', ''l'' \u2192 ''\u00d8''.\n:1b. Suffixation of ''-\u0101''. Often accompanied by:\n::Root vowel change: ''\u016b/o'' \u2192 ''u'', ''e/ai/\u0101/\u012b'' \u2192 ''i''.\n::Insertion of [[semivowel]] ''l'' between such vowel-terminating stems.\n:2. Suffixation of ''-v\u0101'' (in place of ''-\u0101'' if and where it'd occur) for a \"causative\".\n\nThe majority of the following are sets culled from {{Harvcoltxt|Shapiro|2003|p=270}} and {{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|pp=243\u2013244}}. The lack of third members displayed for the ''gh\u016bmn\u0101'' to ''dhuln\u0101'' sets does not imply that they do not exist but that they were simply not listed in the source literature {{Harvcol|Snell|Weightman|1989|p=243}}. Intransitive verbs are coloured <span style=\"color:brown;\">brown</span> while transitives remain the usual black.\n\n*<span style=\"color:brown;\">''girn\u0101''</span> \"to fall\", ''gir\u0101n\u0101'' \"to fell\", ''girv\u0101n\u0101'' \"to cause to be felled\".\n*<span style=\"color:brown;\">''banna''</span> \"to become\", ''ban\u0101n\u0101'' \"to make\", ''banv\u0101n\u0101'' \"to cause to be made\".\n*<span style=\"color:brown;\">''khuln\u0101''</span> \"to open\", ''kholn\u0101'' \"to open\", ''khulv\u0101n\u0101'' \"to cause to be opened\".\n*''s\u012bkhn\u0101'' \"to learn\", ''sikh\u0101n\u0101'' \"to teach\", ''sikhv\u0101n\u0101'' \"to cause to be taught\".\n*''kh\u0101n\u0101'' \"to eat\", ''khil\u0101n\u0101'' \"to feed\", ''khilv\u0101n\u0101'' \"to cause to be fed\".\n*<span style=\"color:brown;\">''bikn\u0101''</span> \"to sell\", ''becn\u0101'' \"to sell\", ''bikv\u0101n\u0101'' \"to cause to be sold\".\n*<span style=\"color:brown;\">''dikhn\u0101/d\u012bkhn\u0101''</span> \"to seem\", ''dekhn\u0101'' \"to see\", ''dikh\u0101n\u0101'' \"to show\", ''dikhv\u0101n\u0101'' \"to cause to be shown\".\n*''kahn\u0101'' \"to say\", <span style=\"color:brown;\">''kahl\u0101n\u0101''</span> \"to be called\".\n*<span style=\"color:brown;\">''gh\u016bmn\u0101''</span> \"to go round\", ''ghum\u0101n\u0101'' \"to make go round\".\n*<span style=\"color:brown;\">''{{IAST|le\u1e6dn\u0101}}''</span> \"to lie down\", ''{{IAST|li\u1e6d\u0101n\u0101}}'' \"to lay down\".\n*<span style=\"color:brown;\">''{{IAST|bai\u1e6dhn\u0101}}''</span> \"to sit\", ''{{IAST|bi\u1e6dh\u0101n\u0101}}'' \"to seat\".\n*<span style=\"color:brown;\">''son\u0101''</span> \"to sleep\", ''sul\u0101n\u0101'' \"to make sleep\".\n*<span style=\"color:brown;\">''dhuln\u0101''</span> \"to wash\", ''dhon\u0101'' \"to wash\".\n*<span style=\"color:brown;\">''{{IAST|\u1e6d\u016b\u1e6dn\u0101}}''</span> \"to break\", ''{{IAST|to\u1e5bn\u0101}}'' \"to break\", ''{{IAST|tu\u1e5b\u0101n\u0101}}'' \"to cause to be broken\".\n\nIn the causative model of \"to cause to be Xed\", the agent takes the postposition ''se''. Thus ''Y se Z banv\u0101n\u0101'' \"to cause Z to be made by Y\" = \"to cause Y to make Z\" = \"to have Z made by Y\" = \"to have Y make Z\", etc.\n<!---Need to add those that change from a to A. Also bolnA/bulAnA/bulvAnA. Change \"The following are sets...\" to \"The majority of the following are sets...\".--->\n\n====Compounds====\n<!---\nStraight from Shapiro\n270:\ndegree of productivity. Considerable attention has been paid by scholars to determining the {{sic|semnatic}} properties contributed by the election of particle V2 verbs for use in particular compounds. In many cases the meaning contributed by V2 element bears scant resemblance to the literal meaning of the V2 element when it occurs as an independent verb. Thus for example, it is not possible to explain the semantic difference between uThnA \"to rise, get up\" and uTh baiThnA \"to get up suddenly, to spring up\" in terms of the semantics of baiThnA \"to sit down\".\n--->\n[[Compound verb]]s, a highly visible feature of Hindi\u2013Urdu grammar, consist of a verbal stem plus an [[auxiliary verb]]. The auxiliary (variously called \"subsidiary\", \"explicator verb\", and \"vector\"<ref name=\"Shapiro2003p269\">{{Harvcoltxt|Shapiro|2003|p=269}}</ref>) loses its own independent meaning and instead \"lends a certain shade of meaning\"<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|p=154}}</ref> to the main or stem verb, which \"comprises the lexical core of the compound\".<ref name=\"Shapiro2003p269\"/> While almost any verb can act as a main verb, there is a limited set of productive auxiliaries.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Shapiro|2003|pp=269\u2013270}}</ref> Shown below are prominent such auxiliaries, with their independent meaning first outlined, followed by their semantic contribution as auxiliaries.\n\n*''j\u0101n\u0101'' \"to go\"; gives a sense of completeness, finality, or change of state. e.g. ''\u0101n\u0101'' \"to come\" \u2192 ''\u0101 j\u0101n\u0101'' \"to come, arrive\"; ''kh\u0101n\u0101'' \"to eat\" \u2192 ''kh\u0101 j\u0101n\u0101'' \"to eat up\"; ''p\u012bn\u0101'' \"to drink\" \u2192 ''p\u012b j\u0101n\u0101'' \"to drink up\"; ''{{IAST|bai\u1e6dhn\u0101}}'' \"to sit\" \u2192 ''{{IAST|bai\u1e6dh j\u0101n\u0101}}'' \"to sit down\"; ''samajhn\u0101'' \"to understand\" \u2192 ''samajh j\u0101n\u0101'' \"to realise\"; ''son\u0101'' \"to sleep\" \u2192 ''so j\u0101n\u0101'' \"to go to sleep\"; ''hon\u0101'' \"to be\" \u2192 ''ho j\u0101n\u0101'' \"to become, happen\".<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|pp=155}}</ref>\n*''len\u0101'' \"to take\"; suggests that the benefit of the action flows towards the doer. e.g. ''{{IAST|pa\u1e5bh len\u0101}}'' \"to read (to/for oneself)\".<ref name=\"Snell&Weightman1989p156\">{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|pp=156}}</ref>\n*''den\u0101'' \"to give\"; suggests that the benefit of the action flows away from the doer. e.g. ''{{IAST|pa\u1e5bh den\u0101}}'' \"to read (out)\".<ref name=\"Snell&Weightman1989p156\"/>\n\nThe above three are the most common of auxiliaries, and the \"least marked\", or \"lexically nearly colourless\".<ref name=\"Schmidt2003p337\">{{Harvcoltxt|Schmidt|2003|pp=337}}</ref> The nuance conveyed by an auxiliary can often be very subtle, and need not always be expressed with different words in English translation. ''len\u0101'' and ''den\u0101'', transitive verbs, occur with transitives, while intransitive ''j\u0101n\u0101'' occurs mostly with intransitives; a compound of a transitive and ''j\u0101n\u0101'' will be grammatically intransitive as ''j\u0101n\u0101'' is.\n\n*''{{IAST|\u1e0d\u0101ln\u0101}}'' \"to throw, pour\"; indicates an action done vigorously, decisively, violently or recklessly;<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|p=220}}</ref> it is an intensifier, showing intensity, urgency, completeness, or violence.<ref name=\"Schmidt2003p338\">{{Harvcoltxt|Schmidt|2003|p=338}}</ref> e.g. ''m\u0101rn\u0101'' \"to strike\" \u2192 ''{{IAST|m\u0101r \u1e0d\u0101ln\u0101}}'' \"to kill\", ''p\u012bn\u0101'' \"to drink\" \u2192 ''{{IAST|p\u012b \u1e0d\u0101ln\u0101}}'' \"to drink down\".\n*''{{IAST|bai\u1e6dhn\u0101}}'' \"to sit\"; implies an action done foolishly or stubbornly;<ref name=\"Snell&Weightman1989p221\">{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|p=221}}</ref> shows speaker disapproval or an impulsive or involuntary action.<ref name=\"Schmidt2003p338\"/> ''kahn\u0101'' \"to say\" \u2192 ''{{IAST|kah bai\u1e6dhn\u0101}}'' \"to blurt out\", ''karn\u0101'' \"to do\" \u2192 ''{{IAST|kar bai\u1e6dhn\u0101}}'' \"to do (as a blunder)\", ''{{IAST|la\u1e5bn\u0101}}'' \"to fight\" \u2192 ''{{IAST|la\u1e5b bai\u1e6dhn\u0101}}'' \"to quarrel (foolishly)\".\n*''{{IAST|pa\u1e5bn\u0101}}'' \"to fall\"; connotes involuntary, sudden, or unavoidable occurrence;<ref name=\"Schmidt2003p337\"/> adds a sense of suddenness or change of state, with its independent/literal meaning sometimes showing through in a sense of downward movement.<ref name=\"Snell&Weightman1989p221\"/>\n*''{{IAST|u\u1e6dhn\u0101}}'' \"to rise\"; functions like an intensifier;<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Schmidt|2003|pp=337\u2013338}}</ref>  suggests inception of action or feeling, with its independent/literal meaning sometimes showing through in a sense of upward movement. e.g. ''jaln\u0101'' \"to burn\" \u2192 ''{{IAST|jal u\u1e6dhn\u0101}}'' \"to burst into flames\", ''nacn\u0101'' \"to dance\" \u2192 ''{{IAST|nac u\u1e6dhn\u0101}}'' \"to break into dance\".<ref name=\"Snell&Weightman1989p221\"/>\n*''{{IAST|sakn\u0101}}'' \"to be able to\"; a modal verb that indicates the capability of performing an action. e.g. ''karn\u0101'' \"to do\" \u2192 ''kar sakn\u0101'' \"to be able to do\", ''dekhn\u0101'' \"to see\" \u2192 ''dekh sakhn\u0101'' \"to be able to see\".\n*''rakhn\u0101'' \"to keep, maintain\"; implies a firmness of action, or one with possibly long-lasting results or implications;<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|p=222}}</ref> occurs with ''len\u0101'' and ''den\u0101'', meaning \"to give/take (as a loan)\", and with other appropriate verbs, showing an action performed beforehand.<ref name=\"Schmidt2003p338\"/>\n*The continuous aspect marker ''rah\u0101'' apparently originated as a compound verb with ''rahn\u0101'' (\"remain\"):  thus ''m\u00e3\u0129 bol rah\u0101 h\u016b\u0303'' = \"I have remained speaking\" \u2192 \"I have continued speaking\" \u2192 \"I am speaking\".  However it has lost the ability to take any form other than the perfective, and is thus considered to have become grammaticalized.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Masica|1991|pp=329}}</ref>\n\nFinally, having to do with the ''manner'' of an occurrence, compounds verbs are mostly used with completed actions and imperatives, and much less with negatives, conjunctives, and contexts continuous or speculative. This is because non-occurrences cannot be described to have occurred in a particular manner.<ref name=\"Snell&Weightman1989p156\"/>\n\n====Conjuncts====\nAnother notable aspect of Hindi\u2013Urdu grammar is that of \"conjunct verbs\", composed of a [[noun]] or [[adjective]] paired up with a general verbalizer, most commonly transitive ''karn\u0101'' \"to do\" or intransitive ''hon\u0101'' \"to be(come)\", functioning in the place of what in [[English language|English]] would be single unified verb.\n\nIn the case of an adjective as the non-verbal element, it is often helps to think of ''karn\u0101'' \"to do\" as supplementally having the senses of \"to cause to be\", \"to make\", \"to render\", etc.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! Adjective !! Conjunct !! Literal !! Meaning\n|-\n|''s\u0101f'' clean||''s\u0101f karn\u0101''||to do clean||to clean\n|-\n|''niyukt/muqarrar'' appointed||''niyukt/muqarrar karn\u0101''||to do appointed||to appoint\n|-\n|''band'' closed||''band hon\u0101''||to become closed||to close\n|-\n|''xatm'' finished||''xatm hon\u0101''||to become finished||to finish\n|}\n\nIn the case of a noun as the non-verbal element, it is treated syntactically as the verb's (direct) object (never taking the ''ko'' marker; governing agreement in perfective and infinitival constructions), and the semantic [[Patient (grammar)|patient]] (or [[Agent (grammar)|agent]]: see ''g\u0101l\u012b kh\u0101n\u0101'' below) of the conjunct verbal expression is often expressed/marked syntactically as a genitive adjunct (''-k\u0101'' ~ ''ke'' ~ ''k\u012b'') of the noun.<ref>{{Harv|Masica|1991|p=368}}</ref><!---more on Masica 368 about \"true conjuncts\": ko shuru (n.) karnA, etc.--->\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! Noun !! Conjunct !! Conjunct + patient !! Literal !! Meaning\n|-\n|''intiz\u0101r'' wait||''intiz\u0101r karn\u0101''||''kis\u012b k\u0101 intiz\u0101r karn\u0101''||to do somebody's wait||to wait for somebody\n|-\n|''istem\u0101l'' use||''istem\u0101l karn\u0101''||''fon k\u0101 istem\u0101l karn\u0101''||to do a phone's use||to use a phone\n|-\n|''b\u0101t'' talk||''b\u0101t karn\u0101''||''Sam\u012br k\u012b b\u0101t karn\u0101''||to do Sameer's talk||to talk about Sameer\n|-\n|''{{IAST|prati\u1e63\u1e6dh\u0101}}'' installation||''{{IAST|prati\u1e63\u1e6dh\u0101nkarn\u0101}}''||''{{IAST|m\u016brti/but k\u012b prati\u1e63\u1e6dh\u0101 karn\u0101}}''||to do an idol's installation||to install an idol\n|-\n|''g\u0101l\u012b'' curse||''g\u0101l\u012b kh\u0101n\u0101''||''sanam k\u012b g\u0101l\u012b kh\u0101n\u0101''||to eat a lover's curse||to be cursed out by one's lover\n|-\n|''tasv\u012br'' picture||''tasv\u012br kh\u012b\u00f1cn\u0101/khicv\u0101n\u0101''||''Ibr\u0101h\u012bm k\u012b tasv\u012br kh\u012b\u00f1cn\u0101/khicv\u0101n\u0101 ''||to pull Ibrahim's picture||to take Ibrahim's picture\n|}\n\nWith [[English language|English]] it is the verb stems themselves that are used.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! Verb stem !! Conjunct !! Meaning\n|-\n|''c\u00eak'' check||''c\u00eak karn\u0101''||to check\n|-\n|''bor'' bore||''bor hon\u0101''||to be bored\n|}\n\n====Passive====\nThe [[Grammatical voice|passive]] construction is [[Periphrasis|periphrastic]]. It is formed from the perfective participle by addition of the auxiliary ''j\u0101n\u0101'' \"to go\"; i.e. ''likhn\u0101'' \"to write\" \u2192 ''likh\u0101 j\u0101n\u0101'' \"to be written\". The agent is marked by the postposition ''se''. Furthermore, both intransitive and transitive verbs may be grammatically passivized to show physical/psychological incapacity, usually in negative sentences. Lastly, intransitives often have a passive sense, or convey unintentional action.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Schmidt|2003|p=331}}</ref>\n\n==Syntax==\nHindustani is an [[subject\u2013object\u2013verb|SOV]] language. It is neither purely left- or right-[[Branching (linguistics)|branching]], and phenomena of both types can be found. The order of constituents in sentences as a whole lacks governing \"hard and fast rules\", and frequent deviations can be found from normative word position, describable in terms of a small number of rules, accounting for facts beyond the pale of the label of \"SOV\".<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Shapiro|2003|p=271}}</ref>\n\n# Indirect objects precede direct objects.\n# Attributive adjectives precede the noun they qualify.\n# Adverbs precede the adjectives they qualify.\n# Negative markers (''nah\u012b\u0303, na, mat'') and interrogatives precede the verb.\n# Interrogatives precede negative markers if both are present.\n# ''ky\u0101'' (\"what?\") as the [[yes-no question]] marker occurs at the ''beginning'' of a clause.\n\n===Possession===\nPossession, reflecting what many other languages indicate via the verb ''to have'', is reflected in Hindustani by the genitive ''k\u0101'' (inflected appropriately) or the postposition ''ke p\u0101s'' (\"near\") and the verb ''hon\u0101''. Possible objects of possession (nouns) fall into two main categories in Hindustani: one for persons such as family members, or body parts, and the other for most inanimate objects, animals, most abstract ideas, and some persons such as servants.\n\n* For indicating possession with objects of the first category, ''k\u0101'' appears after the subject of the possession, followed by the object. With personal pronouns, this requires the use of the possessive pronoun (inflected appropriately). Examples: ''Mer\u012b m\u0101t\u0101 hai'' (\"I have a mother\"), ''\u015aiv k\u012b t\u012bn \u0101\u0303kh\u1ebd ha\u0129'' (\"Shiva has three eyes\").\n* For indicating possession with objects of the second category, the compound postposition ''ke p\u0101s'' (\"near\") is used. For example: ''Mohan ke p\u0101s ek bakr\u012b hai'' (\"Mohan has a goat\", but also \"There is a goat near Mohan\").\n\n===Relativization===\nRather than using relative clauses after nouns, as in English, Hindustani uses correlative clauses. A correlative clause goes before the entire clause, rather than being embedded in the clause next to the noun it relativizes. For example, the following sentence means, \"The girl who is standing is is tall.\"<ref>https://ojs.ub.uni-konstanz.de/jsal/index.php/fasal/article/view/109/67</ref>\n\nJo la\u1e5bk\u012b kha\u1e5b\u012b hai, vo lamb\u012b hai.\n\nwhich girl.F.SG standing.F.SG be.PRS.3.SG., that tall.F.SG be.PRS.SG.\n\nModern Hindi also uses post-noun relative clauses which are similar to English. This may be the result of English influence on the language.<ref>https://brill.com/view/journals/jlc/4/2/article-p250_4.xml</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{Citation\n |last=Masica\n |first=Colin\n |authorlink=Colin Masica\n |year=1991\n |title=The Indo-Aryan Languages\n|place= Cambridge\n |publisher=Cambridge University Press\n |isbn=978-0-521-29944-2\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J3RSHWePhXwC&printsec=frontcover&dq=indo-aryan+languages\n}}.\n*{{Citation\n |last=Schmidt\n |first=Ruth Laila\n |year=2003\n |chapter=Urdu\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jPR2OlbTbdkC&pg=PA286&dq=indo-aryan&sig=BWUDFSCrQPgfbEznzUZcq7B2HnE\n|editor1-last= Cardona\n|editor1-first= George\n|editor2-last= Jain\n|editor2-first= Dhanesh\n |title=The Indo-Aryan Languages\n |publisher=Routledge\n |isbn=978-0-415-77294-5\n |pages=286\u2013350\n}}.\n*{{Citation\n |last=McGregor\n |first=Ronald Stuart\n |year=1995\n |title=Outline of Hindi Grammar\n |publisher=Clarendon Press\n|place=Oxford\n |edition=third\n |isbn=0-19-870008-3\n}}.\n*{{Citation\n |last=Shapiro\n |first=Michael C.\n |year=2003\n |chapter=Hindi\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jPR2OlbTbdkC&pg=PA250&dq=indo-aryan&sig=cUNurxJKkTLfKf8uiMd7pWX2RC0\n|editor1-last= Cardona\n|editor1-first= George\n|editor2-last= Jain\n|editor2-first= Dhanesh\n |title=The Indo-Aryan Languages\n |publisher=Routledge\n |isbn=978-0-415-77294-5\n |pages=250\u2013285\n}}.\n*{{Citation\n|last1= Snell\n|first1= Rupert\n|last2= Weightman\n|first2= Simon\n |year=1989\n |title=[[Teach Yourself]] Hindi\n |publisher=McGraw-Hill\n |edition=2003\n |isbn=978-0-07-142012-9\n}}.\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{citebook|url=https://archive.org/stream/introductiontohi00shakrich#page/8/mode/2up|title=An introduction to the Hindustani language comprising a grammar, and a vocabulary, English and Hindustani : also short stories and dialogues, short stories in Persian and Nagari characters ... and military words of command, Nagari and English|author=Shakespear, John, (1775-1858).|publisher=London : W.H. Allen}}\n*{{citebook|url=https://archive.org/stream/grammarofurduorh00dowsiala#page/n11/mode/2up|title=A grammar of the Urdu or Hindustani language|author=Dowson, John (1820-1881)|publisher= London : K. Paul, Trench, Tr\u00fcbner & Co., ltd. 1908}} (public domain e-book) Contributed by [[University of California]] libraries\n{{Navboxes\n|list =\n{{Hindi topics}}\n{{Urdu topics}}\n{{Indo-Aryan grammars}}\n{{Language grammars}} \n}}\n[[Category:Grammars of specific languages]]\n[[Category:Hindustani language]]\n[[Category:Hindi]]\n[[Category:Urdu]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2016}}\n\n[[Hindustani language|Hindustani]], the [[lingua franca]] of northern India and Pakistan, has two standardised [[Register (sociolinguistics)|register]]s: [[Hindi]] and [[Urdu]]. Grammatical differences between the two standards are minor but each uses its own script: Hindi uses [[Devanagari]] while Urdu uses [[Urdu alphabet|an extended form]] of the [[Perso-Arabic script]], typically in the [[Nasta\u02bfl\u012bq script|Nasta\u02bfl\u012bq]] style.\n\nOn this grammar page [[Hindustani language|Hindustani]] is written in \"standard [[oriental studies|orientalist]]\" [[Transcription (linguistics)|transcription]] as outlined in {{Harvcoltxt|Masica|1991|p=xv}}. Being \"primarily a system of [[transliteration]] from the Indian scripts, [and] based in turn upon [[Sanskrit]]\" (cf. [[IAST]]), these are its salient features: [[subscript]] [[dot (diacritic)|dot]]s for [[retroflex consonant]]s; [[Macron (diacritic)|macron]]s for etymologically, contrastively [[long vowel]]s; ''h'' for [[Aspiration (phonetics)|aspirated]] [[plosive]]s; and [[tilde]]s for [[nasalized vowel]]s.\n\n==Phonology==\n{{main|Hindustani phonology}}\nThe vowels used in Hindustani are the following: {{H:title|/\u0259/|''a''|dotted=no}}, {{H:title|/\u00e4\u02d0/|''\u0101''|dotted=no}}, {{H:title|/\u026a/|''i''|dotted=no}}, {{H:title|/i\u02d0/|''\u012b''|dotted=no}}, {{H:title|/\u028a/|''u''|dotted=no}}, {{H:title|/u\u02d0/|''\u016b''|dotted=no}}, {{H:title|/e\u02d0/|''e''|dotted=no}}, {{H:title|/o\u02d0/|''o''|dotted=no}}, {{H:title|/\u025b\u02d0/|''ai''|dotted=no}}, {{H:title|/\u0254\u02d0/|''au''|dotted=no}}.  Note that the vowels ''a'' ''ai'' ''au'' normally have the pronunciations {{IPA|[\u0259] [\u025b\u02d0] [\u0254\u02d0]}}. [[Consonant]]s are outlined in the table below. Hovering the mouse cursor over them will reveal the appropriate [[International Phonetic Alphabet|IPA]] symbol, while in the rest of the article hovering the mouse cursor over {{H:title||underlined}} forms will reveal the appropriate English [[translation]]. \n\n:::{|class=\"wikitable IPA\" border=\"2\"\n!\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[Bilabial consonant|Bilabial]]\n! [[Labiodental consonant|Labio-<br>dental]]\n! colspan=\"2\" | &nbsp;[[Dental consonant|Dental]]&nbsp;\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[Alveolar consonant|Alveolar]]\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[Retroflex consonant|Retroflex]]\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[Post-alveolar|Post-alv.]]/<br>[[Palatal consonant|Palatal]]\n! colspan=\"2\" | &nbsp;[[Velar consonant|Velar]] &nbsp;\n! [[Uvular consonant|Uvular]]\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[Glottal consonant|Glottal]]\n|- align=center\n! [[Plosive]]\n| {{H:title|/p/|p|dotted=no}}<br>{{H:title|/p\u02b0/|ph|dotted=no}}\n| {{H:title|/b/|b|dotted=no}}<br>{{H:title|/b\u02b1/|bh|dotted=no}}\n|\n| {{H:title|/t\u032a/|t|dotted=no}}<br>{{H:title|/t\u032a\u02b0/|th|dotted=no}}\n| {{H:title|/d\u032a/|d|dotted=no}}<br>{{H:title|/d\u032a\u02b1/|dh|dotted=no}}\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n| {{H:title|/\u0288/|\u1e6d|dotted=no}}<br>{{H:title|/\u0288\u02b0/|\u1e6dh|dotted=no}}\n| {{H:title|/\u0256/|\u1e0d|dotted=no}}<br>{{H:title|/\u0256\u02b1/|\u1e0dh|dotted=no}}\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n| {{H:title|/k/|k|dotted=no}}<br>{{H:title|/k\u02b0/|kh|dotted=no}}\n| {{H:title|/\u0261/|g|dotted=no}}<br>{{H:title|/g\u02b1/|gh|dotted=no}}\n| {{H:title|/q/, often /k/ in Hindi|(q)|dotted=no}}\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n|-align=center\n! [[Affricate consonant|Affricate]]\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n| {{H:title|/t\u0283/|c|dotted=no}}<br>{{H:title|/t\u0283\u02b0/|ch|dotted=no}}\n| {{H:title|/d\u0292/|j|dotted=no}}<br>{{H:title|/d\u0292\u02b1/|jh|dotted=no}}\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n|- align=center\n! [[Nasal stop|Nasal]]\n| colspan=\"2\" | {{H:title|/m/|m|dotted=no}}\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" | {{H:title|/n/|n|dotted=no}}\n| colspan=\"2\" | {{H:title|[\u0273]|(\u1e47)|dotted=no}}\n| colspan=\"2\" | {{H:title|[\u0272]|(\u00f1)|dotted=no}}\n| colspan=\"2\" | {{H:title|[\u014b]|(\u1e45)|dotted=no}}\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n|- align=center\n! [[Fricative]]\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n| {{H:title|/f/|f|dotted=no}}\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n| {{H:title|/s/|s|dotted=no}}\n| {{H:title|/z/|z|dotted=no}}\n| colspan=\"2\" | {{H:title|/\u0283/; [\u0282] before /\u0288, \u0288\u02b0/|(\u1e63)|dotted=no}}\n| {{H:title|/\u0283/|\u015b|dotted=no}}\n| {{H:title|/\u0292/|(\u017a)|dotted=no}}\n| {{H:title|/x/, often [k\u02b0] in Hindi|(x)|dotted=no}}\n| {{H:title|/\u0263/, often [g] in Hindi|(\u0121)|dotted=no}}\n|\n\n| colspan=\"2\" | {{H:title|/\u0266/|h|dotted=no}}\n|- align=center\n! [[Flap consonant|Tap or Flap]]\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" | {{H:title|/\u027e/|r|dotted=no}}\n| colspan=\"2\" | {{H:title|[\u027d]|(\u1e5b)|dotted=no}}<br>{{H:title|[\u027d\u02b1]|(\u1e5bh)|dotted=no}}\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n|- align=center\n! [[Approximant]]\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n| {{H:title|/\u028b/|v|dotted=no}}\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" | {{H:title|/j/|y|dotted=no}}\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n|- align=center\n! [[Lateral approximant|Lateral<br>approximant]]\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" | {{H:title|/l/|l|dotted=no}}\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n|\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n|- align=center\n|}\n\n==Morphology==\n\n===Nouns===\nHindustani distinguishes two [[grammatical gender|genders]] (masculine and feminine), two noun types ([[count noun|count]] and non-count), two [[grammatical number|numbers]] (singular and plural), and three [[grammatical case|case]]s ([[direct case|direct]], [[oblique case|oblique]], and [[vocative case|vocative]]).<ref name=\"Kachru\">{{cite book|last1=Kachru|first1=Yamuna|title=Hindi|date=2006|publisher=John Benjamins Publishing Company|edition=12th|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Hindi.html?id=ooH5VfLTQEQC|isbn=9789027238122}}</ref>{{rp|43}} Nouns may be further divided into two classes based on [[declension]], called type-I (marked) and type-II (unmarked). The basic difference between the two categories is that the former has characteristic [[suffix|termination]]s in the direct singular while the latter does not.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Shapiro|2003|pp=262\u2013263}}</ref>\n\nThe table below displays the suffix paradigms. A [[hyphen]] symbol (for the marked type-I) denotes change from the original termination to another (for example ''la\u1e5bk\u0101'' to ''la\u1e5bke'' in the masculine singular oblique), whereas a [[Plus and minus signs|plus]] sign (for the unmarked type-II) denotes an ending which should be added (''seb'' to ''seb\u00f5'' in the masculine plural oblique).\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" colspan=\"2\"| !! colspan=\"2\"| Singular !! colspan=\"3\"| Plural\n|-\n! Direct !! Oblique/Vocative !! Direct !! Oblique !! Vocative\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Masculine !! I\n| -''\u0101''<br>\u0640\u0627<br>\u093e||colspan=\"2\"|-''e''<br>\u0947/\u0640\u06d2||-''\u00f5''<br>\u094b\u0902/\u0640\u0648\u06ba||-''o''<br>\u094b/\u0640\u0648\n|-\n! II\n|colspan=\"3\"| ||+''\u00f5''<br>\u094b\u0902/\u0640\u0648\u06ba||+''o''<br>\u094b/\u0640\u0648\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Feminine !! I\n|colspan=\"2\"|-''\u012b''<br>\u0940/\u0640\u0650\u06cc<br>-''i''<br>\u093f/\u0640\u0650\u06cc<br>-''iy\u0101''<br>\u092f\u093e\u093f/\u0640\u0650\u06cc\u0627||-''iy\u0101\u0303''<br>\u092f\u093e\u093f\u0901/\u0640\u0650\u06cc\u0627\u06ba||-''iy\u00f5''<br>\u092f\u094b\u093f\u0902/\u0640\u0650\u06cc\u0648\u06ba||-''iyo''<br>\u092f\u094b\u093f/\u0640\u0650\u06cc\u0648\n|-\n! II\n|colspan=\"2\"| ||+''\u1ebd''<br>\u0947\u0902/\u0640\u06cc\u06ba||+''\u00f5''<br>\u094b\u0902/\u0640\u0648\u06ba||+''o''<br>\u094b/\u0640\u0648\n|}\n\nThe next table of noun [[declension]]s, mostly adapted from {{Harvcoltxt|Shapiro|2003|p=263}}, shows the above suffix paradigms in action. Words: ''la\u1e5bk\u0101'' \u0932\u0921\u093c\u0915\u093e/\u0644\u0691\u06a9\u0627 ('boy'), ''ku\u0101\u0303'' \u0915\u0941\u0906\u0901/\u06a9\u0648\u0627\u06ba ('[[Water well|well]]'), ''seb'' \u0938\u0947\u092c/\u0633\u06cc\u0628 ('apple'), ''v\u0101lid'' \u0935\u0932\u093f\u0926/\u0648\u0627\u0644\u062f ('father'), ''c\u0101q\u016b'' \u091a\u093e\u0915\u093c\u0942/\u0686\u0627\u0642\u0648 ('[[penknife]]'), ''\u0101dm\u012b'' \u0906\u0926\u092e\u0940/\u0622\u062f\u0645\u06cc ('man'), ''mitr\u0101'' \u092e\u093f\u0924\u094d\u0930\u093e/\u0645\u062a\u0631\u0627 ('friend'), ''la\u1e5bk\u012b'' \u0932\u0921\u093c\u0915\u0940/\u0644\u0691\u06a9\u06cc ('girl'), ''ci\u1e5biy\u0101'' \u091a\u093f\u0921\u093c\u093f\u092f\u093e/\u0686\u0691\u06cc\u0627 ('[[finch]]'), ''kit\u0101b'' \u0915\u093f\u0924\u093e\u092c/\u06a9\u062a\u0627\u0628 ('book'), ''bh\u0101\u1e63\u0101'' \u092d\u093e\u0937\u093e/\u0628\u06be\u0627\u0634\u0627 ('language'), and ''aurat'' \u0914\u0930\u0924/\u0639\u0648\u0631\u062a ('woman').\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" colspan=\"2\"| !! colspan=\"2\"| Singular !! colspan=\"3\"| Plural\n|-\n! Direct !! Oblique/Vocative !! Direct !! Oblique !! Vocative\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Masculine !! I\n|''la\u1e5bk\u0101'' \u0932\u0921\u093c\u0915\u093e/\u0644\u0691\u06a9\u0627<br>''ku\u0101\u0303''<br>\u0915\u0941\u0906\u0901/\u06a9\u0648\u0627\u06ba {{ref|2|2}}\n|colspan=\"2\"|''la\u1e5bke'' \u0932\u0921\u093c\u0915\u0947/\u0644\u0691\u06a9\u06d2<br>''ku\u1ebd'' \u0915\u0941\u090f\u0901/\u06a9\u0648\u06cc\u06ba\n|''la\u1e5bk\u00f5'' >\u0932\u0921\u093c\u0915\u094b\u0902/\u0644\u0691\u06a9\u0648\u06ba<br>''ku\u00f5'' \u0915\u0941\u0913\u0902/\u06a9\u0648\u0648\u06ba\n|''la\u1e5bko'' \u0932\u0921\u093c\u0915\u094b/\u0644\u0691\u06a9\u0648\n|-\n! II\n|colspan=\"3\"|''seb'' \u0938\u0947\u092c/\u0633\u06cc\u0628<br>''v\u0101lid'' \u0935\u0932\u093f\u0926/\u0648\u0627\u0644\u062f {{ref|3|3}}<br>''c\u0101q\u016b'' \u091a\u093e\u0915\u093c\u0942/\u0686\u0627\u0642\u0648<br>''\u0101dm\u012b'' \u0906\u0926\u092e\u0940/\u0622\u062f\u0645\u06cc\n|''seb\u00f5'' \u0938\u0947\u092c\u094b\u0902/\u0633\u06cc\u0628\u0648\u06ba<br>''v\u0101lid\u00f5'' \u0935\u0932\u093f\u0926\u094b\u0902/\u0648\u0627\u0644\u062f\u0648\u06ba<br>''c\u0101qu\u00f5'' \u091a\u093e\u0915\u093c\u0942\u094b\u0902/\u0686\u0627\u0642\u0648\u0648\u06ba {{ref|4|4}}<br>''\u0101dmiy\u00f5'' \u0906\u0926\u094d\u092e\u093f\u092f\u094b\u0902/\u0622\u062f\u0645\u06cc\u0648\u06ba {{ref|4|4}}\n|<br>''pit\u0101o'' \u092a\u093f\u0924\u093e\u0913/\u067e\u062a\u0627\u0626\u0648<br><br>''\u0101dmiyo'' \u0906\u0926\u094d\u092e\u093f\u092f\u094b/\u0622\u062f\u0645\u06cc\u0648\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Feminine !! I\n|colspan=\"2\"|''la\u1e5bk\u012b'' \u0932\u0921\u093c\u0915\u0940/\u0644\u0691\u06a9\u06cc<br>''ci\u1e5biy\u0101'' \u091a\u093f\u0921\u093c\u093f\u092f\u093e/\u0686\u0691\u06cc\u0627\n|''la\u1e5bkiy\u0101\u0303'' \u0932\u0921\u093c\u0915\u093f\u092f\u093e\u0901/\u0644\u0691\u06a9\u06cc\u0627\u06ba<br>''ci\u1e5biy\u0101\u0303'' \u091a\u093f\u0921\u093c\u093f\u092f\u093e\u0901/\u0686\u0691\u06cc\u0627\u06ba\n|''la\u1e5bkiy\u00f5'' \u0932\u0921\u093c\u0915\u093f\u092f\u094b\u0902/\u0644\u0691\u06a9\u06cc\u0648\u06ba<br>''ci\u1e5biy\u00f5'' \u091a\u093f\u0921\u093c\u093f\u092f\u094b\u0902/\u0686\u0691\u06cc\u0648\u06ba\n|''la\u1e5bkiyo'' \u0932\u0921\u093c\u0915\u093f\u092f\u094b/\u0644\u0691\u06a9\u06cc\u0648\n|-\n! II\n|colspan=\"2\"|''kit\u0101b'' \u0915\u093f\u0924\u093e\u092c/\u06a9\u062a\u0627\u0628<br>''bh\u0101\u1e63\u0101'' \u092d\u093e\u0937\u093e/\u0628\u06be\u0627\u0634\u0627<br>''aurat'' \u0914\u0930\u0924/\u0639\u0648\u0631\u062a\n|''kit\u0101b\u1ebd'' \u0915\u093f\u0924\u093e\u092c\u0947\u0902/\u06a9\u062a\u0627\u0628\u06cc\u06ba<br>''bh\u0101\u1e63\u0101\u1ebd'' \u0915\u093f\u0924\u093e\u092c\u090f\u0901/\u0628\u06be\u0627\u0634\u0627\u0626\u06cc\u06ba{{ref|5|5}}<br>''aurt\u1ebd'' \u0914\u0930\u0924\u0947\u0902/\u0639\u0648\u0631\u062a\u06cc\u06ba\n|''kit\u0101b\u00f5'' \u0915\u093f\u0924\u093e\u092c\u094b\u0902/\u06a9\u062a\u0627\u0628\u0648\u06ba<br>''bh\u0101\u1e63\u0101\u00f5'' \u0915\u093f\u0924\u093e\u092c\u0913\u0902/\u0628\u06be\u0627\u0634\u0627\u0626\u0648\u06ba<br>''aurt\u00f5'' \u0914\u0930\u0924\u094b\u0902/\u0639\u0648\u0631\u062a\u0648\u06ba\n|<br><br>''aurto'' \u0914\u0930\u0924\u094b/\u0639\u0648\u0631\u062a\u0648\n|}\nNotes for noun declension:\n*{{note|1|1}}This is also the ending used for the vocative masculine singular.\n*{{note|2|2}}A small number of marked masculines like ku\u00e3\u0304 display [[nasalization]] of all terminations.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Shapiro|2003|p=262}}</ref>\n*{{note|3|3}}Some masculines ending in ''\u0101'' don't change in the direct plural and fall in the unmarked category. i.e. ''v\u0101lid'' \"father\", ''c\u0101c\u0101'' \"[[uncle]]\", ''r\u0101j\u0101'' \"[[king]]\".<ref name=\"Snell&Weightman1989p24\">{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|p=24}}</ref>\n*{{note|4|4}}Unmarked nouns ending in ''\u016b'' and ''\u012b'' generally shorten this to ''u'' and ''i'' before the oblique (and vocative) plural termination(s), with the latter also inserting the [[semivowel]] ''y''.<ref name=\"Snell&Weightman1989p24\" /><ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|p=43}}</ref><ref name=\"Shapiro2003p263\">{{Harvcoltxt|Shapiro|2003|p=263}}</ref>\n*{{note|5|5}}Many feminine [[Sanskrit]] loanwords such as ''bh\u0101\u1e63\u0101'' ('language') and ''m\u0101t\u0101'' (mother) end in ''\u0101'', therefore the ''\u0101'' is not a reliable indicator of noun gender.<ref name=\"Snell&Weightman1989p24\" />\n*The ''iy\u0101'' ending is also not a reliable indicator of gender or noun type. Some words such as ''pahiy\u0101'' ('wheel') and [[Persian language|Persian]] ''takiy\u0101'' ('pillow') are masculine type-I: ''pahiye'' ('wheels'), ''takiye'' ('pillows'). Feminine loanwords such as [[Arabic language|Arabic]] ''duniy\u0101'' ('world') and [[Sanskrit]] ''kriy\u0101'' ('action') use feminine type-II endings: ''duniy\u0101\u1ebd'' ('worlds'), ''kriy\u0101\u1ebd'' ('actions').\n*In Urdu, many Arabic words retain their Arabic plurals.\n*[[Persian language|Perso]]-[[Arabic language|Arabic]] [[loanword|loan]]s ending in final unpronounced ''h'' are handled as masculine marked nouns.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Schmidt|2003|p=313}}</ref> Hence ''bacca(h)'' \u2192 ''bacc\u0101''. The former is the Urdu spelling, the latter the Hindi.\n*Some Arabic loans may use their original [[Dual (grammatical number)|dual]] and [[plural]] markings. i.e. ''v\u0101lid'' \"father\" \u2192 ''v\u0101lidain'' \"[[parent]]s\".\n\n===Adjectives===\n[[Adjective]]s may be divided into '''declinable''' and '''indeclinable''' categories.<ref name=\"Shapiro2003p264\">{{Harvcoltxt|Shapiro|2003|p=264}}</ref> Declinables are marked, through termination, for the gender, number, case of the nouns they qualify. The set of declinable adjective terminations is similar but greatly simplified in comparison to that of noun terminations \u2014\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto;\"\n! colspan=\"2\"| !! Dir. sg. !! All else\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Decl. !! Masc.\n| -''\u0101''||-''e''\n|-\n! Fem.\n|colspan=\"2\"|-''\u012b''\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"| Indecl.\n|colspan=\"2\"|\n|}\n\nIndeclinable adjectives are completely invariable, and can end in either [[consonant]]s or [[vowel]]s (including ''\u0101'' and ''\u012b ''). A number of declinables display nasalization of all terminations.<ref name=\"Shapiro2003p264\"/> Dir. masc. sg. (''-\u0101'') is the [[citation form]].\n\n*Examples of declinable adjectives: ''ba\u1e5b\u0101'' \"big\", ''cho\u1e6d\u0101'' \"small\", ''mo\u1e6d\u0101'' \"fat\", ''acch\u0101'' \"good\", ''bur\u0101'' \"bad\", ''k\u0101l\u0101'' \"black\", ''\u1e6dha\u1e47\u1e0d\u0101'' \"cold\".\n*Examples of indeclinable adjectives: ''xar\u0101b'' \"bad\", ''s\u0101f'' \"clean\", ''bh\u0101r\u012b'' \"heavy\", ''murd\u0101'' \"dead\", ''sundar'' \"beautiful\", ''p\u0101gal'' \"crazy\", ''l\u0101l'' \"red\".\n\n{|\n|-\n|\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; margin: 1em auto 1em auto;\"\n|+Declinable adjective ''ba\u1e5b\u0101'' \"big\" in attributive use\n! rowspan=\"2\" colspan=\"2\"| !! colspan=\"2\"| Sg. !! colspan=\"3\"| Pl.\n|-\n! Dir. !! Obl. !! Dir. !! Obl. !! Voc.\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| M !! I\n|''ba\u1e5b\u0101 la\u1e5bk\u0101''<br>''ba\u1e5b\u0101 ku\u0101\u0303''\n|colspan=\"2\"|''ba\u1e5be la\u1e5bke''<br>''ba\u1e5be ku\u1ebd''\n|''ba\u1e5be la\u1e5bk\u00f5''<br>''ba\u1e5be ku\u00f5''\n|''ba\u1e5be la\u1e5bko''\n|-\n! II\n|''ba\u1e5b\u0101 seb''<br>''ba\u1e5b\u0101 pit\u0101''<br>''ba\u1e5b\u0101 c\u0101k\u016b''<br>''ba\u1e5b\u0101 \u0101dm\u012b''<br>''ba\u1e5b\u0101 mitra''\n|colspan=\"2\"|''ba\u1e5be seb''<br>''ba\u1e5be pit\u0101''<br>''ba\u1e5be c\u0101k\u016b''<br>''ba\u1e5be \u0101dm\u012b''<br>''ba\u1e5be mitra''\n|''ba\u1e5be seb\u00f5''<br>''ba\u1e5be pit\u0101\u00f5''<br>''ba\u1e5be c\u0101ku\u00f5''<br>''ba\u1e5be \u0101dmiy\u00f5''<br>''ba\u1e5be mitr\u00f5''\n|<br>''ba\u1e5be pit\u0101o''<br><br>''ba\u1e5be \u0101dmiyo''<br>''ba\u1e5be mitro''\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| F !! I\n|colspan=\"2\"|''ba\u1e5b\u012b la\u1e5bk\u012b''<br>''ba\u1e5b\u012b \u015bakti''<br>''ba\u1e5b\u012b ci\u1e5biy\u0101''\n|''ba\u1e5b\u012b la\u1e5bkiy\u0101\u0303''<br>''ba\u1e5b\u012b \u015baktiy\u0101\u0303''<br>''ba\u1e5b\u012b ci\u1e5biy\u0101\u0303''\n|''ba\u1e5b\u012b la\u1e5bkiy\u00f5''<br>''ba\u1e5b\u012b \u015baktiy\u00f5''<br>''ba\u1e5b\u012b ci\u1e5biy\u00f5''\n|''ba\u1e5b\u012b la\u1e5bkiyo''\n|-\n! II\n|colspan=\"2\"|''ba\u1e5b\u012b kit\u0101b''<br>''ba\u1e5b\u012b bh\u0101\u1e63\u0101''<br>''ba\u1e5b\u012b aurat''\n|''ba\u1e5b\u012b kit\u0101b\u1ebd''<br>''ba\u1e5b\u012b bh\u0101\u1e63\u0101\u1ebd''<br>''ba\u1e5b\u012b aurt\u1ebd''\n|''ba\u1e5b\u012b kit\u0101b\u00f5''<br>''ba\u1e5b\u012b bh\u0101\u1e63\u0101\u00f5''<br>''ba\u1e5b\u012b aurt\u00f5''\n|<br><br>''ba\u1e5b\u012b aurto''\n|}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; margin: 1em auto 1em auto;\"\n|+Indeclinable adjective ''xar\u0101b'' \"bad\" in attributive use\n! rowspan=\"2\" colspan=\"2\"| !! colspan=\"2\"| Sg. !! colspan=\"3\"| Pl.\n|-\n! Dir. !! Obl. !! Dir. !! Obl. !! Voc.\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| M !! I\n|''xar\u0101b la\u1e5bk\u0101''<br>''xar\u0101b ku\u0101\u0303''\n|colspan=\"2\"|''xar\u0101b la\u1e5bke''<br>''xar\u0101b ku\u1ebd''\n|''xar\u0101b la\u1e5bk\u00f5''<br>''xar\u0101b ku\u00f5''\n|''xar\u0101b la\u1e5bko''\n|-\n! II\n|colspan=\"3\"|''xar\u0101b seb''<br>''xar\u0101b pit\u0101''<br>''xar\u0101b c\u0101k\u016b''<br>''xar\u0101b \u0101dm\u012b''<br>''xar\u0101b mitra''\n|''xar\u0101b seb\u00f5''<br>''xar\u0101b pit\u0101\u00f5''<br>''xar\u0101b c\u0101ku\u00f5''<br>''xar\u0101b \u0101dmiy\u00f5''<br>''xar\u0101b mitr\u00f5''\n|<br>''xar\u0101b pit\u0101o''<br><br>''xar\u0101b \u0101dmiyo''<br>''xar\u0101b mitro''\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| F !! I\n|colspan=\"2\"|''xar\u0101b la\u1e5bk\u012b''<br>''xar\u0101b \u015bakti''<br>''xar\u0101b ci\u1e5biy\u0101''\n|''xar\u0101b la\u1e5bkiy\u0101\u0303''<br>''xar\u0101b \u015baktiy\u0101\u0303''<br>''xar\u0101b ci\u1e5biy\u0101\u0303''\n|''xar\u0101b la\u1e5bkiy\u00f5''<br>''xar\u0101b \u015baktiy\u00f5''<br>''xar\u0101b ci\u1e5biy\u00f5''\n|''xar\u0101b la\u1e5bkiyo''\n|-\n! II\n|colspan=\"2\"|''xar\u0101b kit\u0101b''<br>''xar\u0101b bh\u0101\u1e63\u0101''<br>''xar\u0101b aurat''\n|''xar\u0101b kit\u0101b\u1ebd''<br>''xar\u0101b bh\u0101\u1e63\u0101\u1ebd''<br>''xar\u0101b aurt\u1ebd''\n|''xar\u0101b kit\u0101b\u00f5''<br>''xar\u0101b bh\u0101\u1e63\u0101\u00f5''<br>''xar\u0101b aurt\u00f5''\n|<br><br>''xar\u0101b aurto''\n|}\n|}\n\nAll adjectives can be used either [[Attributive adjective#Attributive.2C predicative.2C absolute.2C and substantive adjectives|attributively, predicatively, or substantively]]. Substantively they are declined as nouns rather than adjectives.\n\n''s\u0101'' (~ ''se'' ~ ''s\u012b'') is a suffix for adjectives, modifying or lightening their meaning; giving them an \"-ish\" or \"quite\" sense. e.g. ''n\u012bl\u0101'' \"blue\" \u2192 ''n\u012bl\u0101-s\u0101'' \"bluish\". Its emphasis is rather ambiguous, sometimes enhancing, sometimes toning down, the sense of the adjective.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|p=117}}</ref>\n\n====Comparatives and superlatives====\n[[Comparative|Comparison]]s are made by using \"than\" (the [[postposition]] ''se''; [[Hindustani grammar#Postpositions|see below]]), \"more\" (''aur'', ''zy\u0101d\u0101''), and \"less\" (''kam''). The word for \"more\" is optional, while \"less\" is required, so that in the absence of either \"more\" will be inferred.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! Hindustani !! Word order !! Meaning\n|-\n|''G\u012bt\u0101 Gautam se lamb\u012b hai''||Gita Gautam than tall is||Gita is taller than Gautam\n|-\n|''G\u012bt\u0101 Gautam se aur/zy\u0101d\u0101 lamb\u012b hai''||Gita Gautam than more tall is||Gita is more tall than Gautam\n|-\n|''G\u012bt\u0101 Gautam jitn\u012b lamb\u012b hai''|| Gita Gautam as tall is\n||Gita is (just) as tall as Gautam\n|-\n|''G\u012bt\u0101 Gautam se kam lamb\u012b hai''||Gita Gautam than less tall is||Gita is less tall than Gautam\n|}\n\nIn the absence of an object of comparison (\"more\" of course is now no longer optional):\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! Hindustani !! Word order !! Meaning\n|-\n|''chokr\u0101 zy\u0101d\u0101 ba\u1e5b\u0101 hai''||The lad more big is||The lad is bigger\n|-\n|''chokr\u0101 utn\u0101 hi lamb\u0101 hai''|| The lad as just tall is\n||The lad is just as big\n|-\n|''chokr\u0101 kam ba\u1e5b\u0101 hai''||The lad less big is||The lad is less big\n|}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! Hindustani !! Word order !! Meaning\n|-\n|''zy\u0101d\u0101 ba\u1e5b\u0101 chokr\u0101''||The more big lad||The bigger lad\n|-\n|'' ''|| ||The just as big lad\n|-\n|''kam ba\u1e5b\u0101 chokr\u0101''||The less big lad ||The less big lad\n|}\n\n[[Superlative]]s are made through comparisons with \"all\" (''sab''). Comparisons using \"least\" are rare; it is more common to use an antonym.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! Hindustani !! Word order !! Meaning\n|-\n|''kamr\u0101 sabse s\u0101f hai''||The room all than clean is||The room is the cleanest\n|-\n|''kamr\u0101 sabse kam s\u0101f hai''||The room all than less clean is||The room is the least clean\n|-\n| ''kamr\u0101 sabse gand\u0101 hai''||The room all than dirty is||The room is the dirtiest\n|}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! Hindustani !! Word order !! Meaning\n|-\n|''sabse s\u0101f kamr\u0101''||The all than clean room||The cleanest room\n|-\n|''sabse kam s\u0101f kamr\u0101''||The all than less clean room||The least clean room\n|-\n|''sabse gand\u0101 kamr\u0101'' ||The all than dirty room||The dirtiest room\n|}\n\nIn Sanskritized and Persianized [[Register (sociolinguistics)|register]]s of Hindustani, comparative and superlative adjectival forms using suffixes derived from those languages can be found.<ref name=\"Shapiro 2003 265\">{{Harvcoltxt|Shapiro|2003|p=265}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! !! Sanskrit !! Persian\n|-\n|Comp. (\"-er\")||colspan=\"2\"|-''tar''\n|-\n|Sup. (\"-est\")||-''tam''||-''tar\u012bn''\n|}\n\n===Numerals===\n{{main|Hindustani numerals}}\nThe numeral systems of several of the Indo-Aryan languages, including Hindustani and [[Nepali language|Nepali]], are typical [[decimal]] systems, but contracted to the extent that nearly every number 1\u201399 is irregular. The first four [[ordinal number (linguistics)|ordinal numbers]] are also irregular. The suffix ''-v\u0101\u0303'' marks ordinals beginning at the number five.\n\n{| class=wikitable\n|+ 0-5\n! English !! Hindustani Cardinal !! Hindustani Ordinal\n|-\n| zero || ''\u015b\u016bnya'', ''sifar'' || -\n|-\n| one || ''ek'' || ''pahl\u0101'', ''avval''\n|-\n| two || ''do'' || ''d\u016bsr\u0101''\n|-\n| three || ''t\u012bn'' || ''t\u012bsr\u0101''\n|-\n| four || ''ch\u0101r'' || ''cauth\u0101''\n|-\n| five || ''p\u0101\u0303ch'' || ''p\u0101\u0303chv\u0101\u0303''\n|}\n\n===Postpositions===\nThe aforementioned [[inflection]]al [[grammatical case|case]] system only goes so far on its own, and rather serves as that upon which is built a system of [[agglutinative]] [[suffix]]es or [[Grammatical particle|particle]]s known as [[postposition]]s, which parallel [[English language|English]]'s [[preposition]]s. It is their use with a noun or verb that necessitates the noun or verb taking the oblique case (though the bare oblique is also minorly used [[adverb]]ially<ref name=\"Shapiro2003p266\">{{Harvcoltxt|Shapiro|2003|p=266}}</ref>), and it is with them that the locus of grammatical function or \"case-marking\" then lies. There are seven such one-word primary postpositions:\n\n*''k\u0101'' \u2013 [[Genitive case|genitive]] marker; variably declinable in the manner of an adjective. X ''k\u0101/ke/k\u012b'' Y has the sense \"X's Y\", with ''k\u0101/ke/k\u012b'' agreeing with Y.<ref name=\"Shapiro2003p264\"/>\n*''ko'' \u2013 marks the indirect [[Object (grammar)|object]] (hence named  \"[[dative]] marker\"), ''or'', if [[definiteness|definite]] or animate, the direct object.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|p=67}}</ref>\n*''ne'' \u2013 [[Ergative case|ergative]] marker; applied to [[Subject (grammar)|subject]]s of [[Transitivity (grammatical category)|transitive]] [[Perfective aspect|perfective]] [[verb]]s.\n*''se'' \u2013 [[Ablative case|ablative]] marker; has a very wide range of uses and meanings:\n**\"from\";  ''dill\u012b se'' \"from [[Delhi]]\".\n**\"from, of\"; ''{{IAST|tumse \u1e0darn\u0101}}'' \"to fear you\".\n**\"since\"; ''itv\u0101r se'' \"since Sunday\".\n**\"by, with\"; [[Instrumental case|instrumental]] marker.\n**\"by, with, -ly\"; [[adverb]]ial marker.\n**\"than\"; for [[comparative]]s.\n**a minority of verbs use ''se'' rather than ''ko'' to mark their [[Patient (grammar)|patient]]s.\n*''m\u1ebd'' \u2013 \"in\".\n*''par'' \u2013 \"on\".\n*''tak'' \u2013 \"until, up to\".\n\nBeyond these are a large range of compound postpositions, composed of the genitive primary postposition ''k\u0101'' in the oblique form (''ke'', ''k\u012b'') plus an adverb.\n\n*''k\u012b taraf'' \"towards\", ''ke andar'' \"inside\", ''ke \u0101ge'' \"in front of, ahead of\", ''ke \u016bpar'' \"on top of, above\", ''ke n\u012bce'' \"beneath, below\", ''ke p\u012bche'' \"behind\", ''ke b\u0101d'' \"after\", ''ke b\u0101re m\u1ebd'' \"about\", ''ke b\u0101har'' \"outside\", ''ke liye'' \"for\", ''ke s\u0101mne'' \"facing, opposite\", etc.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|pp=80\u201381}}</ref>\n\n===Pronouns===\n\n====Personal====\nHindustani has [[personal pronoun]]s for the first and second persons, while for the third person [[demonstrative]]s are used, which can be categorized [[Deixis|deictically]] as proximate and non-proximate.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Shapiro|2003|pp=264\u2013265}}</ref> [[Pronoun]]s distinguish [[Grammatical case|case]]s of [[Direct case|direct]], [[Oblique case|oblique]], and [[dative]]. The lattermost, often called a set of \"[[Contraction (grammar)|contracted]]\" forms, is in free variation with the oblique case plus dative [[postposition]]. Pronouns do not distinguish [[Grammatical gender|gender]].\n\nAlso displayed in the below table are the [[genitive]] pronominal forms to show that the 1st and 2nd pronouns have their own distinctive forms of ''mer\u0101'', ''ham\u0101r\u0101'',  ''ter\u0101'', ''tumh\u0101r\u0101'' apart from the regular formula of <small>OBL.</small> + ''k\u0101''; as well as the [[ergative case|ergative]] pronominal forms to show that the postposition ''ne'' does not straightforwardly suffix the oblique bases: rather than *''mujh ne'' and *''tujh ne'', direct bases are used giving ''mai ne'' and ''t\u016b ne'', and rather than ''in ne'' and ''un ne'', it's ''inh\u00f5 ne'' and ''unh\u00f5 ne''.\n\n''t\u016b'', ''tum'', and ''\u0101p'' are the three second person pronouns (\"you\"), constituting a threefold scale of sociolinguistic formality: respectively \"intimate\", \"familiar\", and \"polite\". The \"intimate\" is grammatically singular while the \"familiar\" and \"polite\" are grammatically plural.<ref name=\"Shapiro 2003 265\"/> When being referred to in the third person however, only those of the \"polite\" level of formality are grammatically plural.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|p=21}}</ref> The following table is adapted from {{Harvcoltxt|Shapiro|2003|p=265}}.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!rowspan=\"4\"|\n!colspan=\"5\"|Personal\n!colspan=\"4\"|Demonstrative\n!colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"3\"|Relative\n!colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"3\"|Interrogative\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|1st person\n!colspan=\"3\"|2nd person\n!colspan=\"4\"|3rd person\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Singular\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Plural\n!Singular\n!colspan=\"2\"|Plural\n!colspan=\"2\"|Proximal\n!colspan=\"2\"|Non-proximal\n|-\n!Intimate\n!Familiar\n!Polite\n!Singular\n!Plural\n!Singular\n!Plural\n!Singular\n!Plural\n!Singular\n!Plural\n|-\n!Direct\n|{{H:title|I|''m\u00e3\u0129''}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|{{H:title|we/us|''ham''}}\n|{{H:title|thou|''t\u016b''}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|{{H:title|you|''tum''}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|{{H:title|you|''\u0101p''}}\n|colspan=\"2\"|{{H:title|he/she/it/this/they/these|''ye''}}||colspan=\"2\"|{{H:title|he/she/it/that/they/those|''vo''}}\n|colspan=\"2\"|{{H:title|[those] who/[those] that|''jo''}}\n|colspan=\"2\"|{{H:title|who(?)|''kaun''}}, {{H:title|what(?)|''ky\u0101''}}\n|-\n!Oblique\n|{{H:title|me|''mujh''}}||{{H:title|thee|''tujh''}}||{{H:title|him/her/it/this|''is''}}||{{H:title|them/these|''in''}}||{{H:title|him/her/it/that|''us''}}||{{H:title|them/those|''un''}}||{{H:title|[he/she] whom/[that] which|''jis''}}||{{H:title|[those] whom/[those] which|''jin''}}||{{H:title|whom(?)/what(?)|''kis''}}||{{H:title|whom(?)/which ones(?)|''kin''}}\n|-\n!Dative\n|{{H:title|to me|''mujhe''}}||{{H:title|to us|''ham\u1ebd''}}||{{H:title|to thee|''tujhe''}}||{{H:title|to you|''tumh\u1ebd''}}||{{H:title|to you|''\u0101p ko''}}||{{H:title|to him/to her/to it/to this|''ise''}}||{{H:title|to them/to these|''inh\u1ebd''}}||{{H:title|to him/to her/to it/to that|''use''}}||{{H:title|to them/to those|''unh\u1ebd''}}\n|{{H:title|[he/she] to whom/[that] to which|''jise''}}||{{H:title|[those] to whom/[those] to which|''jinh\u1ebd''}}||{{H:title|to whom(?)/to what(?)|''kise''}}||{{H:title|to whom(?)/to which ones(?)|''kinh\u1ebd''}}\n|-\n!Genitive\n|{{H:title|My/Mine|''mer\u0101''}}||{{H:title|our(s)|''ham\u0101r\u0101''}}||{{H:title|thy/thine|''ter\u0101''}}\n|{{H:title|your(s)|''tumh\u0101r\u0101''}}||{{H:title|your/s|''\u0101p k\u0101''}}\n|{{H:title|his/her(s)/its/of this|''is k\u0101''}}||{{H:title|their(s)/of these|''in k\u0101''}}||{{H:title|his/her(s)/its/of that|''us k\u0101''}}||{{H:title|their(s)/of those|''un k\u0101''}}\n|{{H:title|[he/she] whose|''jis k\u0101''}}||{{H:title|[those] whose|''jin k\u0101''}}||{{H:title|whose(?)/which one's(?)|''kis k\u0101''}}||{{H:title|whose(?)/which ones'(?)|''kin k\u0101''}}\n|-\n!Ergative\n|{{H:title|I (have/had done something to an object)|''m\u00e3\u0129 ne''}}||{{H:title|we (have/had done something to an object)|''ham ne''}}||{{H:title|thou (hast/hadst done something to an object)|''t\u016b ne''}}||{{H:title|you (have/had done something to an object)|''tum ne''}}||{{H:title|you (have/had done something to an object)|''\u0101p ne''}}||{{H:title|he/she/it/this (has/had done something to an object)|''is ne''}}||{{H:title|they/these (have/had done something to an object)|''inh\u00f5 ne''}}\n|{{H:title|he/she/it/that (has/had done something to an object)|''us ne''}}||{{H:title|they/those (have/had done something to an object)|''unh\u00f5 ne''}}||{{H:title|[he/she] who/[that] which  (has/had done something to an object)|''jis ne''}}||{{H:title|[those] who/[those] that (have/had done something to an object)|''jinh\u00f5 ne''}}||{{H:title|who/what (has/had done something to an object?)|''kis ne''}}||{{H:title|who/which ones (has/have/had done something to an object?)|''kinh\u00f5 ne''}}\n|}\nNotes for pronouns:\n*Postpositions are treated as [[bound morpheme]]s after pronouns in Hindi, but as separate words in Urdu.<ref name=\"Schmidt2003p293\">{{Harvcoltxt|Schmidt|2003|p=293}}</ref> \n*The varying forms for the 3rd pn. dir. constitute one of the small number of grammatical differences between Hindi and Urdu. ''yah'' \"this\" / ''ye'' \"these\" / ''vah'' \"that\" / ''ve'' \"those\" is the ''literary'' set for Hindi while ''ye'' \"this, these\" / ''vo'' \"that, those\" is the set for Urdu and ''spoken'' (and also often written) Hindi.\n*The above [[Hindustani grammar#Postpositions|section on postpositions]] noted that ''ko'' (the dative case) marks direct objects if [[definiteness|definite]]. As \"the most specific thing of all is an individual\", persons (or their pronouns) nearly always take the dative case or postposition.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|p=68}}</ref>\n*it is very common practice to use plural pronouns (and their accompanying conjugation) in polite situations, thus ''tum'' can be used in the second person when referring to one person. Similarly, some speakers prefer plural ''ham'' over singular ''m\u00e3\u0129''. This is usually not quite the same as the \"[[Pluralis majestatis|royal we]]\"; it is rather colloquial.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|p=106}}</ref>\n*''ko\u012b'' and ''kuch'' are [[indefinite pronoun]]s/[[Quantifier (linguistics)|quantifier]]s. As pronouns ''ko\u012b'' is used for [[Animacy|animate]]s (\"someone\") and ''kuch'' for inanimates (\"something\").<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|p=88}}</ref> As quantifiers/adjectives ''ko\u012b'' is used for singular [[count noun]]s and ''kuch'' for [[mass noun]]s and plural count nouns. ''ko\u012b'' takes the form ''kis\u012b'' in the oblique. The form ''ka\u012b'' \"several\" is partially a plural equivalent to ''ko\u012b''.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|p=89}}</ref> ''kuch'' can also act as an [[adverb]], qualifying an adjective, meaning \"rather\". ''ko\u012b'' preceding a number takes the meaning of \"about, approximately\". In this usage it does not oblique to ''kis\u012b''.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|p=90}}</ref>\n*''apn\u0101'' is a (genitive) [[reflexive pronoun]]: \"my/your/etc. (own)\".<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|p=79}}</ref> Using non-reflexive and reflexive together gives emphasis; e.g. ''mer\u0101 apn\u0101'' \"my (very) own\".<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|p=80}}</ref> ''xud'', ''\u0101p'', and ''svayam'' are some (direct; non-genitive) others: \"my/your/etc.-self\".<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|p=198}}</ref> Bases for oblique usage are usually ''apne'' or ''apne \u0101p''. The latter alone can also mean \"of one's own accord\"; ''\u0101pas m\u1ebd'' means \"among/between themselves\".<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|p=199}}</ref>\n\n====Derivates====\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! rowspan=\"2\"| !! rowspan=\"2\"|Interrogative !! rowspan=\"2\"|Relative !! colspan=\"2\"|Demonstrative\n|-\n! Prox. !! Non-prox.\n|-\n!Time\n|{{H:title|when?|''kab''}}||{{H:title|when|''jab''}}\n|{{H:title|now|''ab''}}||{{H:title|then|''tab''}}\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Place\n|{{H:title|where?|''kah\u0101\u0303''}}||{{H:title|where|''jah\u0101\u0303''}}\n|{{H:title|here|''yah\u0101\u0303''}}||{{H:title|there|''vah\u0101\u0303''}}\n|-\n|{{H:title|whither?|''kidhar''}}||{{H:title|whither|''jidhar''}}\n|{{H:title|hither|''idhar''}}||{{H:title|thither|''udhar''}}\n|-\n!Quantity\n|{{H:title|how much/many?|''kitn\u0101''}}||{{H:title|as much/many|''jitn\u0101''}}\n|{{H:title|this much/many|''itn\u0101''}}||{{H:title|that much/many|''utn\u0101''}}\n|-\n!Quality\n|''kais\u0101''||''jais\u0101''||''ais\u0101''||''vais\u0101''\n|-\n!Manner\n|''kaise''||''jaise''||''aise''||''vaise''\n|}\n<!---gujarati677, schmidt323--->\n\n===Adverbs===\nHindustani has few underived forms.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Schmidt|2003|p=322}}</ref> [[Adverb]]s may be derived in ways such as the following \u2014\n*Simply obliquing some nouns and adjectives: ''n\u012bc\u0101'' \"low\" \u2192 ''n\u012bce'' \"down\", ''s\u012bdh\u0101'' \"straight\" \u2192 ''s\u012bdhe'' \"straight\", ''dh\u012br\u0101'' \"slow\" \u2192 ''dh\u012bre'' \"slowly\", ''sawer\u0101'' \"morning\" \u2192 ''sawere'' \"in the morning\", ''ye taraf'' \"this direction\" \u2192 ''is taraf'' \"in this direction\", ''kalkatt\u0101'' \"[[Calcutta]]\" \u2192 ''kalkatte'' \"to Calcutta\".\n*Nouns using a postposition such as ''se'' \"by, with, -ly\": ''zor'' \"force\" \u2192 ''zor se'' \"forcefully\" (lit. \"with force\"), ''dhy\u0101n'' \"attention\" \u2192 ''dhy\u0101n se'' \"attentively\" (lit. \"with attention\").\n*Adjectives using postpositional phrases involving \"way, manner\": ''acch\u0101'' \"good\" \u2192 ''acch\u012b tarah se'' \"well\" (lit. \"by/in a good way\"), ''x\u0101s'' \"special\" \u2192 ''x\u0101s taur par'' \"especially\" (lit. \"on a special way\").\n*Verbs in conjunctive form: ''h\u00e3s'' \"laugh\" \u2192 ''h\u00e3s kar'' \"laughingly\" (lit. \"having laughed\"), ''maharb\u0101n\u012b kar'' \"do kindness\" \u2192 ''maharb\u0101n\u012b kar ke'' \"kindly, please\" (lit. \"having done kindness\").<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|pp=150}}</ref>\n*Formative suffixes from Sanskrit or Perso-Arabic in higher registers of Hindi or Urdu. Skt. ''sambhava'' \"possible\" + ''{{IAST|-ta\u1e25}}'' \u2192 ''{{IAST|sambhavata\u1e25}}'' \"possibly; Ar. ''ittif\u0101q'' \"chance\" + ''-an'' \u2192 ''ittif\u0101qan'' \"by chance\".<ref name=\"Shapiro2003p266\"/>\n\n===Verbs===\n\n====Overview====\nThe Hindustani [[verb]]al system is largely structured around a combination of [[Grammatical aspect|aspect]] and [[Grammatical tense|tense]]/[[Grammatical mood|mood]]. Like the nominal system, the Hindustani verb involves successive layers of (inflectional) elements to the right of the [[Root (linguistics)|lexical base]].<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Masica|1991|p=257}}</ref>\n\nHindustani has 3 aspects: [[perfective]], [[habitual]], and [[Continuous and progressive aspects|continuous]], each having overt morphological correlates.<ref name=\"Shapiro2003p266\"/> These are [[participle]] forms, inflecting for [[Grammatical gender|gender]] and [[Grammatical number|number]] by way of a vowel termination, like adjectives.<ref name=\"Schmidt2003p323\"/> The perfective, though displaying a \"number of irregularities and morphophonemic adjustments\", is the simplest, being just the [[Word stem|verb stem]] followed by the agreement vowel. The habitual forms from the [[imperfective]] participle; verb stem, plus -''t''-, then vowel. The continuous forms [[Periphrasis|periphrastic]]ally through [[compound verb|compound]]ing ([[Hindustani grammar#Compounds|see below]]) with the perfective of ''rahn\u0101'' \"to stay\".\n\nDerived from ''hon\u0101'' \"to be\" are five [[copula (linguistics)|copula]] forms: [[Present tense|present]], [[Past tense|past]], [[subjunctive]], presumptive, [[contrafactual]] ([[List of acronyms and initialisms: A#AK|aka]] \"past conditional\"). Used both in basic predicative/existential sentences and as [[Auxiliary verb|verbal auxiliaries]] to aspectual forms, these constitute the basis of tense and mood.\n\nNon-aspectual forms include the [[infinitive]], the [[Imperative mood|imperative]], and the [[conjunction (grammar)|conjunctive]]. Mentioned morphological conditions such the subjunctive, \"presumptive\", etc. are applicable to both copula roots for auxiliary usage with aspectual forms ''and'' to non-copula roots directly for often unspecified (non-aspectual) [[Finite verb|finite]] forms.\n\n[[Finite verb]]al [[Agreement (linguistics)|agreement]] is with the nominative [[Subject (grammar)|subject]], except in the ''[[Transitive verb|transitive]] perfective'', where it is with the [[direct object]], with the erstwhile subject taking the [[ergative case|ergative]] construction ''-ne'' (see [[Hindustani grammar#Postpositions|postpositions]] above). The perfective aspect thus displays [[split ergativity]].\n\nTabled below on the left are the paradigms for adjectival [[Agreement (linguistics)|concord]] (<sup>A</sup>), here only slightly different from that introduced [[Hindustani grammar#Adjectives|previously]]: the f. pl. can nasalize under certain conditions. To the right are the paradigms for [[Grammatical person|personal]] concord (<sup>P</sup>), used by the subjunctive.\n\n{|\n|-\n|\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! (A) !! Sg. !! Pl.\n|-\n! Masc.\n| -''\u0101''||-''e''\n|-\n! Fem.\n| -''\u012b''||-''\u012b( \u0303)''\n|}\n|\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! (P) !! 1st. !! 2nd. !! 3rd.\n|-\n!Sg.\n| -''\u016b\u0303''||colspan=\"2\"|-''e''\n|-\n!Pl.\n| -''\u1ebd''|| -''o/\u1ebd''|| -''\u1ebd''\n|}\n|}\n\n====Forms====\nThe sample verb is intransitive ''dau\u1e5bn\u0101'' \"to run\", and the sample inflection is 3rd. masc. sg. (<sup>P</sup> = ''e'', <sup>A</sup> = ''\u0101'') where applicable.\n\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"10\" cellspacing=\"1\"\n|-\n! !!Non-aspectual !!Aspectual\n|-\n![[Non-finite verb|Non-finite]]\n|\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto\"\n!Root\n||{{mono|*}} ||{{H:title|run|''dau\u1e5b''}}\n|-\n!Infinitive/<br>Gerund/<br>Obligatory\n||{{mono|*-n\u0101}} ||{{H:title|to run / running|''dau\u1e5bn\u0101''}}\n|-\n!Obl. Infinitive\n||{{mono|*-ne}} ||''dau\u1e5bne''\n|-\n!Conjunctive\n||{{mono|*-kar, *-ke}} ||{{H:title|having run|''dau\u1e5bkar'', ''dau\u1e5bke''}}\n|-\n!Agentive/<br>Prospective\n||{{mono|*-ne v\u0101l-<sup>A</sup>, *-nev\u0101l-<sup>A</sup>}} ||{{H:title|runner / about to run|''dau\u1e5bne v\u0101l\u0101'', ''dau\u1e5bnev\u0101l\u0101''}}\n|}\n|\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto\"\n|+Adjectivals.\n!Perfective\n||{{mono|*-<sup>A</sup> (hu-<sup>A</sup>)}} ||{{H:title|run|''dau\u1e5b\u0101'' (''hu\u0101'')}}\n|-\n!Imperfective\n||{{mono|*-t-<sup>A</sup> (hu-<sup>A</sup>)}} ||{{H:title|running|''dau\u1e5bt\u0101'' (''hu\u0101'')}}\n|}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto\"\n|+Adverbial. Obl. of adjectival.\n|-\n!Imperfective\n||{{mono|*-t-e (hu-e)}} ||''dau\u1e5bte hue''\n|}\n|-\n!Finite\n|\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto\"\n|-\n!Contingent Future\n||{{mono|*-<sup>P</sup>}} ||{{H:title|(if ...) were to run / (then ...) will run|''dau\u1e5be''}}\n|-\n!Definite Future\n||{{mono|*-<sup>P</sup>-g-<sup>A</sup>}} ||{{H:title|will run|''dau\u1e5beg\u0101''}}\n|}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto\"\n|+Imperatives.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Shapiro|2003|p=268}}</ref>\n|-\n!Intimate\n||{{mono|*}} ||''dau\u1e5b''\n|-\n!Familiar\n||{{mono|*-o}} ||''dau\u1e5bo''\n|-\n!Polite\n||{{mono|*-iye}} ||''dau\u1e5biye''\n|-\n!Deferred\n||{{mono|*-n\u0101}} ||''dau\u1e5bn\u0101''\n|-\n!Deferential\n||{{mono|*-iye g\u0101}} ||''dau\u1e5biye g\u0101''\n|}\n|\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto\"\n|+Aspectuals plotted against copulas.\n! colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\"| !! Perfective !! Habitual !! Continuous\n|-\n|{{mono|*-<sup>A</sup>}}\n|{{mono|*-t-<sup>A</sup>}}\n|{{mono|* rah-<sup>A</sup>}}\n|-\n!Present\n|{{mono|[[#endnote_10|h-?]]}}\n|{{H:title|has run|''dau\u1e5b\u0101 hai''}}\n|{{H:title|runs|''dau\u1e5bt\u0101 hai''}}\n|{{H:title|is running|''dau\u1e5b rah\u0101 hai''}}\n|-\n!Past\n|{{mono|{{H:title|was; were|th-<sup>A</sup>}}}}\n|{{H:title|had run|''dau\u1e5b\u0101 th\u0101''}}\n|{{H:title|used to run|''dau\u1e5bt\u0101 th\u0101''}}\n|{{H:title|was running|''dau\u1e5b rah\u0101 th\u0101''}}\n|-\n!Subjunctive\n|{{mono|[[#endnote_10|ho-<sup>P</sup>]]}}\n|{{H:title|(if ...) has run|''dau\u1e5b\u0101 ho''}}\n|{{H:title|(if ...) runs (regularly)|''dau\u1e5bt\u0101 ho''}}\n|{{H:title|(if ...) is running|''dau\u1e5b rah\u0101 ho''}}\n|-\n!Presumptive\n|{{mono|{{H:title|must be|ho-<sup>P</sup> g-<sup>A</sup>}}}}\n|{{H:title|has presumably run|''dau\u1e5b\u0101 ho g\u0101''}}\n|{{H:title|presumably runs|''dau\u1e5bt\u0101 ho g\u0101''}}\n|{{H:title|is presumably running|''dau\u1e5b rah\u0101 ho g\u0101''}}\n|-\n!Contrafactual\n|{{mono|ho-t-<sup>A</sup>}}\n|{{H:title|(if ...) had run / (then ...) would have run|''dau\u1e5b\u0101 hot\u0101''}}\n|{{H:title|(if ...) used to run / (then ...) would have run (regularly)|''dau\u1e5bt\u0101 hot\u0101''}}\n|{{H:title|(if ...) had been running / (then ...) would have been running|''dau\u1e5b rah\u0101 hot\u0101''}}\n|-\n!Unspecified\n|\n|{{H:title|ran|''dau\u1e5b\u0101''}}\n|''dau\u1e5bt\u0101''\n|\n|}\n|}\n\n'''Notes'''\n*Much of the above chart information derives from {{Harvcoltxt|Masica|1991|pp=292\u2013294, 323\u2013325}}.\n*The future tense is formed by adding the suffix ''g\u0101'' (~ ''ge'' ~ ''g\u012b'') to the subjunctive, which is a contraction of ''ga\u0101'' (= ''gay\u0101'', perfective participle of ''j\u0101n\u0101'' \"to go\").<ref name=\"Schmidt2003p323\">{{Harvcoltxt|Schmidt|2003|p=323}}</ref> The future suffix, conjunctive participle, and suffix ''v\u0101l\u0101'' are treated as bound morphemes in written Hindi, but as separate words in written Urdu.<ref name=\"Schmidt2003p293\"/> \n*{{note|10}}The present copula ({{mono|h-?}}) seems not to follow along the lines of the regular <sup>P</sup> system of terminations; while the subjunctive copula ({{mono|ho-<sup>P</sup>}}) is thoroughly irregular. So here are all of their forms.\n:{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! rowspan=\"2\"| !!colspan=\"3\"| Sg !! colspan=\"4\"| Pl.\n|-\n! 1st. !! 2nd. !! 3rd. !! 1st. !! colspan=\"2\"| 2nd. !! 3rd.\n|-\n! Pron. !! ''m\u00e3\u0129'' !! ''t\u016b'' !! ''vo'' !! ''ham'' !! ''tum'' !! ''\u0101p'' !! ''vo''\n|-\n! Pres.\n|{{H:title|am|''h\u016b\u0303''}}||colspan=\"2\"|{{H:title|are, is|''hai''}}||{{H:title|are|''h\u00e3\u0129''}}\n|{{H:title|are|''ho''}}||colspan=\"2\"|{{H:title|are|''h\u00e3\u0129''}}\n|-\n! Subj.\n|''h\u016b\u0303''||colspan=\"2\"|''ho''||''h\u00f5''||''ho''||colspan=\"2\"|''h\u00f5''\n|}\n*For the 1. subj. sg. copula {{Harvcoltxt|Schmidt|2003|pp=324}} and {{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|pp=113, 125}} list ''h\u016b\u0303'' while {{Harvcoltxt|Shapiro|2003|p=267}} lists ''ho\u016b\u0303''.\n*{{Harvcoltxt|Shapiro|2003|p=268}} lists the polite imperative ending as ''-iye'', while {{Harvcoltxt|Schmidt|2003|p=330}} lists it as ''-ie'' but ''-iye'' after ''\u0101, o, \u016b''.\n*The euphonic [[Semivowel|glide]] ''y'' is inserted in perfective participles between prohibited [[vowel cluster]]s. It is historically the remnant of the old perfective marker.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Schmidt|2003|pp=324}}</ref> The clusters are ''a + \u0101'', ''\u0101 + \u0101'', ''o + \u0101'', and ''\u012b + \u0101'', resulting in ''\u0101y\u0101'', ''ay\u0101'', ''oy\u0101'', ''iy\u0101''.<ref name=\"Schmidt2003p328\"/> e.g. ''kh\u0101'''y'''\u0101/kh\u0101'''y'''e/kh\u0101\u012b/kh\u0101\u012b\u0303'' (''kh\u0101''- \"eat\").\n*In addition, the combinations ''\u012b + \u012b'' and ''i + \u012b'' give ''\u012b''.<ref name=\"Schmidt2003p328\"/> e.g. ''piy\u0101/piye/p'''\u012b'''/p'''\u012b\u0303''''' (''p\u012b-'' \"drink\").\n*As stated, agreement in the transitive perfective is with the direct object, with the erstwhile subject taking the ergative postposition ''ne''. If however the direct object takes the postposition ''ko'' (marking [[definiteness]]), or if no direct object is expressed, then agreement neutralizes to default m. sg. ''-\u0101''.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|p=140}}</ref>\n*Is this regard, there are a small number of verbs that while perhaps logically transitive still do not take ''ne'' and continue to agree with the subject, in the perfective. e.g. ''l\u0101n\u0101'' \"to bring\", ''bh\u016bln\u0101'' \"to forget\", ''miln\u0101'' \"to meet\", etc.\n<!--- perhaps Ergative points belong to Syntax\nalso discuss: forms both intransitive/transitive\n--->\n*Besides supplying the copulas, ''hon\u0101'' \"to be\" can be used aspectually: ''hu\u0101'' \"happened, became\"; ''hot\u0101'' \"happens, becomes, is\"; ''ho rah\u0101'' \"happening, being\".\n*''-ke'' can be used as a colloquial alternative to ''-kar'' for the conjunctive participle of any verb.  But for ''karn\u0101'' it is the only possible form; ''karke'', not *''karkar''.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|p=149}}</ref>\n*Hindustani displays a very small number of irregular forms, spelled out in the cells below.\n:{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Root !! rowspan=\"2\"| Perf.<br>Stem<br><ref name=\"Schmidt2003p328\">{{Harvcoltxt|Schmidt|2003|p=328}}</ref> !! colspan=\"2\"| Imperative<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|p=64}}</ref>\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Subj.<br>Stem<br><ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|pp=113, 125}}</ref>\n|-\n!Fam. !!Pol.\n|-\n|''ho-'' \"be\"||''hu-''|| || ||\n|-\n|''j\u0101-'' \"go\"||''ga-''{{ref|7}}|| || ||\n|-\n|''kar-'' \"do\"||''ki-''|| ||''k\u012bjie'' ||\n|-\n|''de-'' \"give\"||''di-''||''do''||''d\u012bjie''||''d-''\n|-\n|''le-'' \"take\"||''li-''||''lo''||''l\u012bjie''||''l-''\n|-\n|''p\u012b-'' \"drink\"|| || ||''p\u012bjie''\n|}\n*{{note|7}} However, it is ''j\u0101-'' that is used as the perfective stem in the rare instance of an intransitive verb like ''j\u0101n\u0101'' being expressed passively, such as in a passivized imperative/subjunctive construction: ''ghar j\u0101y\u0101 j\u0101e?'' \"Shall [we] go home?\" (lit. \"Shall home be gone to [by us]?\").<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|p=179}}</ref>\n\n====Causatives====\nTransitives or [[causative]]s are morphologically contrastive in Hindustani, leading to the existence of related verb sets divisible along such lines. While the derivation of such forms shows patterns, they do reach a level of variegation so as to make it somewhat difficult to outline all-encompassing rules. Furthermore, some sets may have as many as four to five distinct members; also, the meaning of certain members of given sets may be idiosyncratic.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Shapiro|2003|p=270}}</ref>\n\nStarting from intransitive or transitive verb stems further transitive/causative stems are produced according to these assorted rules \u2014\n:1a. Root vowel change: ''a'' \u2192 ''\u0101'', ''u/\u016b'' \u2192 ''o'', ''i/\u012b'' \u2192 ''e''. Sometimes accompanied by root final consonant change: ''k'' \u2192 ''c'', ''{{IAST|\u1e6d}}'' \u2192 ''{{IAST|\u1e5b}}'', ''l'' \u2192 ''\u00d8''.\n:1b. Suffixation of ''-\u0101''. Often accompanied by:\n::Root vowel change: ''\u016b/o'' \u2192 ''u'', ''e/ai/\u0101/\u012b'' \u2192 ''i''.\n::Insertion of [[semivowel]] ''l'' between such vowel-terminating stems.\n:2. Suffixation of ''-v\u0101'' (in place of ''-\u0101'' if and where it'd occur) for a \"causative\".\n\nThe majority of the following are sets culled from {{Harvcoltxt|Shapiro|2003|p=270}} and {{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|pp=243\u2013244}}. The lack of third members displayed for the ''gh\u016bmn\u0101'' to ''dhuln\u0101'' sets does not imply that they do not exist but that they were simply not listed in the source literature {{Harvcol|Snell|Weightman|1989|p=243}}. Intransitive verbs are coloured <span style=\"color:brown;\">brown</span> while transitives remain the usual black.\n\n*<span style=\"color:brown;\">''girn\u0101''</span> \"to fall\", ''gir\u0101n\u0101'' \"to fell\", ''girv\u0101n\u0101'' \"to cause to be felled\".\n*<span style=\"color:brown;\">''banna''</span> \"to become\", ''ban\u0101n\u0101'' \"to make\", ''banv\u0101n\u0101'' \"to cause to be made\".\n*<span style=\"color:brown;\">''khuln\u0101''</span> \"to open\", ''kholn\u0101'' \"to open\", ''khulv\u0101n\u0101'' \"to cause to be opened\".\n*''s\u012bkhn\u0101'' \"to learn\", ''sikh\u0101n\u0101'' \"to teach\", ''sikhv\u0101n\u0101'' \"to cause to be taught\".\n*''kh\u0101n\u0101'' \"to eat\", ''khil\u0101n\u0101'' \"to feed\", ''khilv\u0101n\u0101'' \"to cause to be fed\".\n*<span style=\"color:brown;\">''bikn\u0101''</span> \"to sell\", ''becn\u0101'' \"to sell\", ''bikv\u0101n\u0101'' \"to cause to be sold\".\n*<span style=\"color:brown;\">''dikhn\u0101/d\u012bkhn\u0101''</span> \"to seem\", ''dekhn\u0101'' \"to see\", ''dikh\u0101n\u0101'' \"to show\", ''dikhv\u0101n\u0101'' \"to cause to be shown\".\n*''kahn\u0101'' \"to say\", <span style=\"color:brown;\">''kahl\u0101n\u0101''</span> \"to be called\".\n*<span style=\"color:brown;\">''gh\u016bmn\u0101''</span> \"to go round\", ''ghum\u0101n\u0101'' \"to make go round\".\n*<span style=\"color:brown;\">''{{IAST|le\u1e6dn\u0101}}''</span> \"to lie down\", ''{{IAST|li\u1e6d\u0101n\u0101}}'' \"to lay down\".\n*<span style=\"color:brown;\">''{{IAST|bai\u1e6dhn\u0101}}''</span> \"to sit\", ''{{IAST|bi\u1e6dh\u0101n\u0101}}'' \"to seat\".\n*<span style=\"color:brown;\">''son\u0101''</span> \"to sleep\", ''sul\u0101n\u0101'' \"to make sleep\".\n*<span style=\"color:brown;\">''dhuln\u0101''</span> \"to wash\", ''dhon\u0101'' \"to wash\".\n*<span style=\"color:brown;\">''{{IAST|\u1e6d\u016b\u1e6dn\u0101}}''</span> \"to break\", ''{{IAST|to\u1e5bn\u0101}}'' \"to break\", ''{{IAST|tu\u1e5b\u0101n\u0101}}'' \"to cause to be broken\".\n\nIn the causative model of \"to cause to be Xed\", the agent takes the postposition ''se''. Thus ''Y se Z banv\u0101n\u0101'' \"to cause Z to be made by Y\" = \"to cause Y to make Z\" = \"to have Z made by Y\" = \"to have Y make Z\", etc.\n<!---Need to add those that change from a to A. Also bolnA/bulAnA/bulvAnA. Change \"The following are sets...\" to \"The majority of the following are sets...\".--->\n\n====Compounds====\n<!---\nStraight from Shapiro\n270:\ndegree of productivity. Considerable attention has been paid by scholars to determining the {{sic|semnatic}} properties contributed by the election of particle V2 verbs for use in particular compounds. In many cases the meaning contributed by V2 element bears scant resemblance to the literal meaning of the V2 element when it occurs as an independent verb. Thus for example, it is not possible to explain the semantic difference between uThnA \"to rise, get up\" and uTh baiThnA \"to get up suddenly, to spring up\" in terms of the semantics of baiThnA \"to sit down\".\n--->\n[[Compound verb]]s, a highly visible feature of Hindi\u2013Urdu grammar, consist of a verbal stem plus an [[auxiliary verb]]. The auxiliary (variously called \"subsidiary\", \"explicator verb\", and \"vector\"<ref name=\"Shapiro2003p269\">{{Harvcoltxt|Shapiro|2003|p=269}}</ref>) loses its own independent meaning and instead \"lends a certain shade of meaning\"<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|p=154}}</ref> to the main or stem verb, which \"comprises the lexical core of the compound\".<ref name=\"Shapiro2003p269\"/> While almost any verb can act as a main verb, there is a limited set of productive auxiliaries.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Shapiro|2003|pp=269\u2013270}}</ref> Shown below are prominent such auxiliaries, with their independent meaning first outlined, followed by their semantic contribution as auxiliaries.\n\n*''j\u0101n\u0101'' \"to go\"; gives a sense of completeness, finality, or change of state. e.g. ''\u0101n\u0101'' \"to come\" \u2192 ''\u0101 j\u0101n\u0101'' \"to come, arrive\"; ''kh\u0101n\u0101'' \"to eat\" \u2192 ''kh\u0101 j\u0101n\u0101'' \"to eat up\"; ''p\u012bn\u0101'' \"to drink\" \u2192 ''p\u012b j\u0101n\u0101'' \"to drink up\"; ''{{IAST|bai\u1e6dhn\u0101}}'' \"to sit\" \u2192 ''{{IAST|bai\u1e6dh j\u0101n\u0101}}'' \"to sit down\"; ''samajhn\u0101'' \"to understand\" \u2192 ''samajh j\u0101n\u0101'' \"to realise\"; ''son\u0101'' \"to sleep\" \u2192 ''so j\u0101n\u0101'' \"to go to sleep\"; ''hon\u0101'' \"to be\" \u2192 ''ho j\u0101n\u0101'' \"to become, happen\".<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|pp=155}}</ref>\n*''len\u0101'' \"to take\"; suggests that the benefit of the action flows towards the doer. e.g. ''{{IAST|pa\u1e5bh len\u0101}}'' \"to read (to/for oneself)\".<ref name=\"Snell&Weightman1989p156\">{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|pp=156}}</ref>\n*''den\u0101'' \"to give\"; suggests that the benefit of the action flows away from the doer. e.g. ''{{IAST|pa\u1e5bh den\u0101}}'' \"to read (out)\".<ref name=\"Snell&Weightman1989p156\"/>\n\nThe above three are the most common of auxiliaries, and the \"least marked\", or \"lexically nearly colourless\".<ref name=\"Schmidt2003p337\">{{Harvcoltxt|Schmidt|2003|pp=337}}</ref> The nuance conveyed by an auxiliary can often be very subtle, and need not always be expressed with different words in English translation. ''len\u0101'' and ''den\u0101'', transitive verbs, occur with transitives, while intransitive ''j\u0101n\u0101'' occurs mostly with intransitives; a compound of a transitive and ''j\u0101n\u0101'' will be grammatically intransitive as ''j\u0101n\u0101'' is.\n\n*''{{IAST|\u1e0d\u0101ln\u0101}}'' \"to throw, pour\"; indicates an action done vigorously, decisively, violently or recklessly;<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|p=220}}</ref> it is an intensifier, showing intensity, urgency, completeness, or violence.<ref name=\"Schmidt2003p338\">{{Harvcoltxt|Schmidt|2003|p=338}}</ref> e.g. ''m\u0101rn\u0101'' \"to strike\" \u2192 ''{{IAST|m\u0101r \u1e0d\u0101ln\u0101}}'' \"to kill\", ''p\u012bn\u0101'' \"to drink\" \u2192 ''{{IAST|p\u012b \u1e0d\u0101ln\u0101}}'' \"to drink down\".\n*''{{IAST|bai\u1e6dhn\u0101}}'' \"to sit\"; implies an action done foolishly or stubbornly;<ref name=\"Snell&Weightman1989p221\">{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|p=221}}</ref> shows speaker disapproval or an impulsive or involuntary action.<ref name=\"Schmidt2003p338\"/> ''kahn\u0101'' \"to say\" \u2192 ''{{IAST|kah bai\u1e6dhn\u0101}}'' \"to blurt out\", ''karn\u0101'' \"to do\" \u2192 ''{{IAST|kar bai\u1e6dhn\u0101}}'' \"to do (as a blunder)\", ''{{IAST|la\u1e5bn\u0101}}'' \"to fight\" \u2192 ''{{IAST|la\u1e5b bai\u1e6dhn\u0101}}'' \"to quarrel (foolishly)\".\n*''{{IAST|pa\u1e5bn\u0101}}'' \"to fall\"; connotes involuntary, sudden, or unavoidable occurrence;<ref name=\"Schmidt2003p337\"/> adds a sense of suddenness or change of state, with its independent/literal meaning sometimes showing through in a sense of downward movement.<ref name=\"Snell&Weightman1989p221\"/>\n*''{{IAST|u\u1e6dhn\u0101}}'' \"to rise\"; functions like an intensifier;<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Schmidt|2003|pp=337\u2013338}}</ref>  suggests inception of action or feeling, with its independent/literal meaning sometimes showing through in a sense of upward movement. e.g. ''jaln\u0101'' \"to burn\" \u2192 ''{{IAST|jal u\u1e6dhn\u0101}}'' \"to burst into flames\", ''nacn\u0101'' \"to dance\" \u2192 ''{{IAST|nac u\u1e6dhn\u0101}}'' \"to break into dance\".<ref name=\"Snell&Weightman1989p221\"/>\n*''{{IAST|sakn\u0101}}'' \"to be able to\"; a modal verb that indicates the capability of performing an action. e.g. ''karn\u0101'' \"to do\" \u2192 ''kar sakn\u0101'' \"to be able to do\", ''dekhn\u0101'' \"to see\" \u2192 ''dekh sakhn\u0101'' \"to be able to see\".\n*''rakhn\u0101'' \"to keep, maintain\"; implies a firmness of action, or one with possibly long-lasting results or implications;<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Snell|Weightman|1989|p=222}}</ref> occurs with ''len\u0101'' and ''den\u0101'', meaning \"to give/take (as a loan)\", and with other appropriate verbs, showing an action performed beforehand.<ref name=\"Schmidt2003p338\"/>\n*The continuous aspect marker ''rah\u0101'' apparently originated as a compound verb with ''rahn\u0101'' (\"remain\"):  thus ''m\u00e3\u0129 bol rah\u0101 h\u016b\u0303'' = \"I have remained speaking\" \u2192 \"I have continued speaking\" \u2192 \"I am speaking\".  However it has lost the ability to take any form other than the perfective, and is thus considered to have become grammaticalized.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Masica|1991|pp=329}}</ref>\n\nFinally, having to do with the ''manner'' of an occurrence, compounds verbs are mostly used with completed actions and imperatives, and much less with negatives, conjunctives, and contexts continuous or speculative. This is because non-occurrences cannot be described to have occurred in a particular manner.<ref name=\"Snell&Weightman1989p156\"/>\n\n====Conjuncts====\nAnother notable aspect of Hindi\u2013Urdu grammar is that of \"conjunct verbs\", composed of a [[noun]] or [[adjective]] paired up with a general verbalizer, most commonly transitive ''karn\u0101'' \"to do\" or intransitive ''hon\u0101'' \"to be(come)\", functioning in the place of what in [[English language|English]] would be single unified verb.\n\nIn the case of an adjective as the non-verbal element, it is often helps to think of ''karn\u0101'' \"to do\" as supplementally having the senses of \"to cause to be\", \"to make\", \"to render\", etc.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! Adjective !! Conjunct !! Literal !! Meaning\n|-\n|''s\u0101f'' clean||''s\u0101f karn\u0101''||to do clean||to clean\n|-\n|''niyukt/muqarrar'' appointed||''niyukt/muqarrar karn\u0101''||to do appointed||to appoint\n|-\n|''band'' closed||''band hon\u0101''||to become closed||to close\n|-\n|''xatm'' finished||''xatm hon\u0101''||to become finished||to finish\n|}\n\nIn the case of a noun as the non-verbal element, it is treated syntactically as the verb's (direct) object (never taking the ''ko'' marker; governing agreement in perfective and infinitival constructions), and the semantic [[Patient (grammar)|patient]] (or [[Agent (grammar)|agent]]: see ''g\u0101l\u012b kh\u0101n\u0101'' below) of the conjunct verbal expression is often expressed/marked syntactically as a genitive adjunct (''-k\u0101'' ~ ''ke'' ~ ''k\u012b'') of the noun.<ref>{{Harv|Masica|1991|p=368}}</ref><!---more on Masica 368 about \"true conjuncts\": ko shuru (n.) karnA, etc.--->\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! Noun !! Conjunct !! Conjunct + patient !! Literal !! Meaning\n|-\n|''intiz\u0101r'' wait||''intiz\u0101r karn\u0101''||''kis\u012b k\u0101 intiz\u0101r karn\u0101''||to do somebody's wait||to wait for somebody\n|-\n|''istem\u0101l'' use||''istem\u0101l karn\u0101''||''fon k\u0101 istem\u0101l karn\u0101''||to do a phone's use||to use a phone\n|-\n|''b\u0101t'' talk||''b\u0101t karn\u0101''||''Sam\u012br k\u012b b\u0101t karn\u0101''||to do Sameer's talk||to talk about Sameer\n|-\n|''{{IAST|prati\u1e63\u1e6dh\u0101}}'' installation||''{{IAST|prati\u1e63\u1e6dh\u0101nkarn\u0101}}''||''{{IAST|m\u016brti/but k\u012b prati\u1e63\u1e6dh\u0101 karn\u0101}}''||to do an idol's installation||to install an idol\n|-\n|''g\u0101l\u012b'' curse||''g\u0101l\u012b kh\u0101n\u0101''||''sanam k\u012b g\u0101l\u012b kh\u0101n\u0101''||to eat a lover's curse||to be cursed out by one's lover\n|-\n|''tasv\u012br'' picture||''tasv\u012br kh\u012b\u00f1cn\u0101/khicv\u0101n\u0101''||''Ibr\u0101h\u012bm k\u012b tasv\u012br kh\u012b\u00f1cn\u0101/khicv\u0101n\u0101 ''||to pull Ibrahim's picture||to take Ibrahim's picture\n|}\n\nWith [[English language|English]] it is the verb stems themselves that are used.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! Verb stem !! Conjunct !! Meaning\n|-\n|''c\u00eak'' check||''c\u00eak karn\u0101''||to check\n|-\n|''bor'' bore||''bor hon\u0101''||to be bored\n|}\n\n====Passive====\nThe [[Grammatical voice|passive]] construction is [[Periphrasis|periphrastic]]. It is formed from the perfective participle by addition of the auxiliary ''j\u0101n\u0101'' \"to go\"; i.e. ''likhn\u0101'' \"to write\" \u2192 ''likh\u0101 j\u0101n\u0101'' \"to be written\". The agent is marked by the postposition ''se''. Furthermore, both intransitive and transitive verbs may be grammatically passivized to show physical/psychological incapacity, usually in negative sentences. Lastly, intransitives often have a passive sense, or convey unintentional action.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Schmidt|2003|p=331}}</ref>\n\n==Syntax==\nHindustani is an [[subject\u2013object\u2013verb|SOV]] language. It is neither purely left- or right-[[Branching (linguistics)|branching]], and phenomena of both types can be found. The order of constituents in sentences as a whole lacks governing \"hard and fast rules\", and frequent deviations can be found from normative word position, describable in terms of a small number of rules, accounting for facts beyond the pale of the label of \"SOV\".<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Shapiro|2003|p=271}}</ref>\n\n# Indirect objects precede direct objects.\n# Attributive adjectives precede the noun they qualify.\n# Adverbs precede the adjectives they qualify.\n# Negative markers (''nah\u012b\u0303, na, mat'') and interrogatives precede the verb.\n# Interrogatives precede negative markers if both are present.\n# ''ky\u0101'' (\"what?\") as the [[yes-no question]] marker occurs at the ''beginning'' of a clause.\n\n===Possession===\nPossession, reflecting what many other languages indicate via the verb ''to have'', is reflected in Hindustani by the genitive ''k\u0101'' (inflected appropriately) or the postposition ''ke p\u0101s'' (\"near\") and the verb ''hon\u0101''. Possible objects of possession (nouns) fall into two main categories in Hindustani: one for persons such as family members, or body parts, and the other for most inanimate objects, animals, most abstract ideas, and some persons such as servants.\n\n* For indicating possession with objects of the first category, ''k\u0101'' appears after the subject of the possession, followed by the object. With personal pronouns, this requires the use of the possessive pronoun (inflected appropriately). Examples: ''Mer\u012b m\u0101t\u0101 hai'' (\"I have a mother\"), ''\u015aiv k\u012b t\u012bn \u0101\u0303kh\u1ebd ha\u0129'' (\"Shiva has three eyes\").\n* For indicating possession with objects of the second category, the compound postposition ''ke p\u0101s'' (\"near\") is used. For example: ''Mohan ke p\u0101s ek bakr\u012b hai'' (\"Mohan has a goat\", but also \"There is a goat near Mohan\").\n\n===Relativization===\nRather than using relative clauses after nouns, as in English, Hindustani uses correlative clauses. A correlative clause goes before the entire clause, rather than being imbeded in the clause next to the noun it relativizes. For example, the following sentence means, \"The girl who is standing is is tall.\"<ref>https://ojs.ub.uni-konstanz.de/jsal/index.php/fasal/article/view/109/67</ref>\n\nJo la\u1e5bk\u012b kha\u1e5b\u012b hai, vo lamb\u012b hai.\n\nwhich girl.F.SG standing.F.SG be.PRS.3.SG., that tall.F.SG be.PRS.SG.\n\nModern Hindi also uses post-noun relative clauses which are similar to English. This may be the result of English influence on the language.<ref>https://brill.com/view/journals/jlc/4/2/article-p250_4.xml</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{Citation\n |last=Masica\n |first=Colin\n |authorlink=Colin Masica\n |year=1991\n |title=The Indo-Aryan Languages\n|place= Cambridge\n |publisher=Cambridge University Press\n |isbn=978-0-521-29944-2\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J3RSHWePhXwC&printsec=frontcover&dq=indo-aryan+languages\n}}.\n*{{Citation\n |last=Schmidt\n |first=Ruth Laila\n |year=2003\n |chapter=Urdu\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jPR2OlbTbdkC&pg=PA286&dq=indo-aryan&sig=BWUDFSCrQPgfbEznzUZcq7B2HnE\n|editor1-last= Cardona\n|editor1-first= George\n|editor2-last= Jain\n|editor2-first= Dhanesh\n |title=The Indo-Aryan Languages\n |publisher=Routledge\n |isbn=978-0-415-77294-5\n |pages=286\u2013350\n}}.\n*{{Citation\n |last=McGregor\n |first=Ronald Stuart\n |year=1995\n |title=Outline of Hindi Grammar\n |publisher=Clarendon Press\n|place=Oxford\n |edition=third\n |isbn=0-19-870008-3\n}}.\n*{{Citation\n |last=Shapiro\n |first=Michael C.\n |year=2003\n |chapter=Hindi\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jPR2OlbTbdkC&pg=PA250&dq=indo-aryan&sig=cUNurxJKkTLfKf8uiMd7pWX2RC0\n|editor1-last= Cardona\n|editor1-first= George\n|editor2-last= Jain\n|editor2-first= Dhanesh\n |title=The Indo-Aryan Languages\n |publisher=Routledge\n |isbn=978-0-415-77294-5\n |pages=250\u2013285\n}}.\n*{{Citation\n|last1= Snell\n|first1= Rupert\n|last2= Weightman\n|first2= Simon\n |year=1989\n |title=[[Teach Yourself]] Hindi\n |publisher=McGraw-Hill\n |edition=2003\n |isbn=978-0-07-142012-9\n}}.\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{citebook|url=https://archive.org/stream/introductiontohi00shakrich#page/8/mode/2up|title=An introduction to the Hindustani language comprising a grammar, and a vocabulary, English and Hindustani : also short stories and dialogues, short stories in Persian and Nagari characters ... and military words of command, Nagari and English|author=Shakespear, John, (1775-1858).|publisher=London : W.H. Allen}}\n*{{citebook|url=https://archive.org/stream/grammarofurduorh00dowsiala#page/n11/mode/2up|title=A grammar of the Urdu or Hindustani language|author=Dowson, John (1820-1881)|publisher= London : K. Paul, Trench, Tr\u00fcbner & Co., ltd. 1908}} (public domain e-book) Contributed by [[University of California]] libraries\n{{Navboxes\n|list =\n{{Hindi topics}}\n{{Urdu topics}}\n{{Indo-Aryan grammars}}\n{{Language grammars}} \n}}\n[[Category:Grammars of specific languages]]\n[[Category:Hindustani language]]\n[[Category:Hindi]]\n[[Category:Urdu]]\n", "name_user": "Bellowhead678", "label": "safe", "comment": "imbeded->embedded -Fix a typo in one click", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hindustani_grammar"}
